column168: UNIT #1 WAS TRAVELING S/B ON THE MAINE TURNPIKE. UNIT #1 EXITED THE TURNPIKE AT EXIT 5. THE COLLISION IGNITED FUEL CARRIED BY UNIT #1, RESULTING IN THE DEATH OF THE DRIVER AND THE TOTAL LOSS OF THE VEHICLE.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING BOX WAS NOTICED ON FLOOR UPSIDE DOWN AND WET.  BOX HAD FALLEN DURING TRANSIT AND LID CAME LOOSE ON (1) 1 GALLON JUG. APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO TRAILER FLOOR.  SPILLAGE AND CONTAINER WAS CONTAINED AND PREPARED FOR DISPOSAL.

DRUMS IN NOSE OF DELIVERY TRAILER FELL OVER WHILE IN BETWEEN STEPS. DRUM #1 ROLLED TO REAR OF TRAILER BREAKING INSIDE OF DOOR. PUNCTURE HOLE CAUSED DURING ROLLING OR IMPACT. DRUM #2 TIPPED OVER ON PALLET CAUSING PINCH ON DRUM. DRIVER RETURNED TO FACILITY AND DRUMS SECURED ON DOCK. TRAILER LESS THAN 1/2 GALLON TOTAL SPILLAGE.FREIGHT TO BE PROPERLY SECURED IN LOAD AND NOT LOADED ON PALLETS.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: DURING ROUTINE CHECK DRIVER FOUND LEAKAGE ON RIGHT SIDE OF REAR OUTSIDE TRAILER. UPON OPENING TRAILER THE LAST DRUM ON RIGHT WAS LEAKING. DRIVER PUT OIL DRY/CAT LITTER AROUND THE LEAKAGE WHICH CONTAINED THE LEAK. DRIVER WAS 100 MILES FROM RECEIVER.. RECEIVER KEPT DEFECTIVE DRUM.

column42: CHEMICAL AMMUNITION, NONEXPLOSIVE (CONTAINING A POISON B MATERIAL)
column168: 2 BATTERIES WERE TURNED OVER IN TRANSIT. RECEIVER PUT NEUTRALIZER (SODA ASH POWDER) ON THE SPILL & TRAILER WASHED OUT.

ONE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS TERMINAL IN POOLER, GEORGIA.  THE RELEASE WAS NOTICED AT THE CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS TERMINAL UPON UNLOADING THE CARGO. LESS THAN ONE QUART WAS RELEASED TO THE WOOD TRAILER FLOOR BEFORE THE CF EMPLOYEES TURNED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE.  SWS LOCATED IN SAVANNAH, GEORGIA, WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE TO OVERPACK THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A 85 GALLON DRUM.  SWS ARRIVED ON SITE, OVERPACKED THE DRUM INTO A NEW 85 GALLON OVERPACK, AND LEFT THE SITE.  THE DRUM WAS TO BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE CAN BE AVOIDED BY UTILIZING MORE CAUTION WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT WITH THE USE OF THE FORKLIFT.

THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT DURING UNLOADING. FORKLIFT SAFETY PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN REVIEWED WITH THE WAREHOUSE STAFF AND MORE STRINGENT SAFETY MEASURES HAVE BEEN PUT IN PLACE. THE SPILL WAS REMEDIATED ON-SITE BY CEMS AND THE RESULTING WASTE WILL BE SENT TO AN EPA APPROVED FACILITY FOR INCINERATION.

column58: Hose; Liner; Loading or Unloading Lines
column168: THE DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING THE PRODUCT. HE WAS APPROXIMATELY HALF WAY DONE WHEN THE ELBOW THAT CONNECTS THE INTERNAL VALVE TO THE EXTERNAL VALVE FAILED. THE DRIVER NOTICED THE FAILURE IMMEDIATELY AND STOPPED THE UNLOADING PROCESS. CLEAN UP OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS IMMEDIATELY PERFORMED. THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE TANKER. ANOTHER DRIVER AND TANKER WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING PRODUCT AND TO FINISH UNLOADING. THE ELBOW THAT FAILED WAS REPLACED AND SENT TO THE SUPPLIER TO SEE WHAT CAN BE DONE TO HELP PREVENT FUTURE FAILURES OF THIS TYPE.

column168: WHILE LOADING THE CARGO TANK, LEVEL DEVICE MALFUNCTIONED. CARGO TANK OVERFILLED. EXCESS WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE STOCK TANKS. SPILLAGE WAS BIOEMEDIATED PER THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.

A SULFURIC ACID TANK LOCATED AT THE CENTRAL SX/EW WAS OVERFLOWED WHILE A TANKER TRUCK WAS FILLING THE TANK.  THE TANK OVERFLOWED TO A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA WITH A DISCHARGE LINE THAT HAD DRAINED TO A PROCESS SOLUTION POND.  THE AREA WHERE THE DISCHARGE LINE WAS CONNECTED TO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT DEVELOPED A LEAK THAT ALLOWED SULFURIC ACID TO ESCAPE THE CONTAINMENT AND REPORT TO THE GROUND OUTSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA. AFTER REVIEWING THE INCIDENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 4,394 POUNDS OF SULFURIC ACID WAS RELEASED.  THIS IS GREATER THAN THE INITIAL 3,100 POUNDS ESTIMATED WHEN THE SPILL WAS REPORTED.  THE RELEASE WAS NOT TO WATERS OF THE UNITED STATES AND WAS COMPLETELY CONTAINED ON PDMI PROPERTY. THE POOLED SOLUTION WAS ROUTED TO A PROCESS SOLUTION POND AND THE SOIL THAT WAS CONTAMINATED FROM THE CONTACT WITH THE SULFURIC ACID WAS EXCAVATED. THE EXCAVATED SOIL WAS PLACED ON LOW-GRADE LEACH STOCKPILES AND ANY ACID PRESENT WILL BE RECOVERED THROUGH THE LEACHING PROCESS.  THERE ARE NO KNOWN OR ANTICIPATED ACUTE OR CHRONIC HEALTH RISKS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS RELEASE.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO CITY CENTER 600 SIDE TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER.  WEARING PPE, I DISCOVERED A 5-PART FLAMMABLE LIQUID THAT WAS STAINED ON TOP OF THE BOX. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE BOX WAS DISCOVERED CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT.  ONE INNER PAIL WAS LEAKING.  THE BOX WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER.  PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

WHILE DELIVERING AT CUSTOMER AND FINISHED WITH UNLOADING INTO THE TOP OF TANK WHICH IS LOCATED 100' FEET AWAY FROM THE DRIVER, THE UNLOADER ASKED OUR DRIVER TO BLOW OUT HIS LINES.  DUE TO NO VENTING SETUP OR/ NOT INSTALLED IN THE TANK THE PRODUCT OVERSPRAYED THE LOADING HOLE WHEN THE TANK WAS FULL.  SEVERAL PEOPLE GOT SPRAYED, ONLY ONE PERSON WENT THE ER HOSPITAL FOR PRODUCT IN HIS RIGHT EYE.  HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.

THE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE FLANGE THAT HAD BEEN LOOSENED WHILE PREPPING THE TANK CAR FOR OFF-LOADING.   THE FLANGE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CONTRACT CLEAN-UP CREW ARRIVED  AT THE SCENE AT 1340 HOURS.  THE CREW CONTAINED THE SPILL AND REMOVED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  THE RE-RAILING CREW CLEARED THE TRACK BY LATE AFTERNOON THE FOLLOWING DAY, AND THE CARS WERE RELEASED TO DESTINATION. THE SHIPPER CONTACTED RESCAR TO INVESTIGATE AND MAKE REPAIRS.  RESCAR FOUND A VAPOR LEAK AROUND THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE FLANGE AND STUDS.  THEY TIGHTENED THE STUD BOLTS ON THE FLANGE BUT THIS DID NOT STOP THE VAPOR RELEASE.  RESCAR DID NOT REPLACE THE FLANGE GASKET BECAUSE THE STUD BOLTS COULD NOT BE REMOVED ACCOUNT THE BOLTS WERE BADLY CORRODED.  THEY APPLIED STEEL EXPOXY AROUND THE FLANGE WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE TEMPORARY REPAIRS MADE. THE SHIPPER OBTAINED AN FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY (FRA 01081470 TO MOVE THE CAR TO DESTINATION. NARRI: 5(4+3+0) X (2+0) =70  CAUSE CODE: 293

SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, FERGUSON-HARBOUR, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED INSIDE THE CONTAINER DUE TO INADEQUATE BLOCKING AND BRACING ALLOWING ONE DRUM TO TURN OVER AND LEAK FROM A CRIMPED AREA  AROUND THE LID. column168: (A/B) GATX 27503 AND TILX 200126 WERE NOTED BY CARRIER PERSONNEL EMITTING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CARS WERE ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, IT CORPORATION, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING:  GATX 27503, DEFECTIVE FILL HOLE GASKET, 3 OF 3 FILL HOLE COVER BOLTS LESS THAN HAND TIGHT.  TILX 200126, DEFECTIVE FILL HOLE GASKET, 4 OF 4 VAPOR LINE MOUNTING FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE.  ALL DEFICIENCIES WERE CORRECTED AND THE CARS WERE SAFE FOR MOVEMENT.

SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, IT CORPORATION, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING:  GATX 27503, DEFECTIVE FILL HOLE GASKET, 3 OF 3 FILL HOLE COVER BOLTS LESS THAN HAND TIGHT. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: INTERMODAL CONTAINER CBHU 72813 WAS NOTED LEAKING MATERIAL FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, REMTECH ENGINEERS, RESPONDED AND FOUND ONE PLASTIC 55 GALLON DRUM LEAKING DUE TO A NAIL PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER WERE DOUBLE STACKED WITH THE LEAKING DRUM ON THE BOTTOM, THE BOTTOM, THE WEIGHT OF THE DRUM ON TOP CAUSED THE BOTTOM DRUM TO COLLAPSE AS THE CONTENTS ESCAPED. THIS SHIPMENT WAS A MIXED LOAD OF HAZARDOUS AND NON-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN THE SAME TYPE PACKAGE.  A SECOND DRUM CONTAINING NON-HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FAILED IN THE SAME MANOR. THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE REMOVED AND OVERPACKED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER WERE DECONTAMINATED AND TRANSFERRED TO OTHER CONTAINERS FOR DELIVERY AFTER PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING WERE APPLIED.  THE CAUSE OF THE FAILURE OF BOTH DRUMS WERE PROTRUDING NAIL HEADS FROM THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUMS.

column168: WHILE IN TRANSPORT FROM THE SHIPPER TO CONSIGNEE THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE HEARD WHAT SOUNDED LIKE A TIRE BLOW OUT.  HE THEN PULLED OFF THE ROADWAY TO INVESTIGATE AND DISCOVERED 1 OF THE 5 PACKAGES OF THE TRAILER TO BE VENTING AND LEAKING MATERIALS.  THE DRIVER THEN GATHERED TOGETHER EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION, BILL OF LADING AND MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS AND CONTACTED VIA CELLULAR PHONE HIS DISPATCH OFFICE.  DISPATCH THEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER.  SHIPPER THEN MADE REPORT TO NRC REFERENCE NUMBER 575898. EMERGENCY RESPONDERS FROM THE SHIPPER AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE THEN DISPATCHED TO THE INCIDENT SITE FOR CONTAINMENT AND ISOLATION OF THE AREA. PRODUCT RELEASED DISSIPATED UPON EXPOSURE TO AMBIENT AIR.  SINCE INCIDENT IT WAS DETERMINED THAT RUPTURE DISC  FAILED DUE TO CORROSION.  ALL OTHER CARGO TANKS IN SAME SERVICE HAVE BEEN PULLED OUT-OF-SERVICE FOR INSPECTION.
column172: Seamless steel, made of definitely prescribed steels over 1000 pounds water volume

column168: THE CAPS/TOPS ON 3 OF THE INNER CONTAINERS LEAKED TO THE OUTER PACKAGE AND ERASED ALL OF THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE INFORMATION ON ALL PAPERWORK. THERE WAS NO INFORMATION INSIDE THE PACKAGE ABOUT THE SHIPPER OR CONSIGNEE. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE RAPA STATION'S SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST PER FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP GUIDELINES. FEDEX ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT WILL WORK WITH THE RAPA STATION ON DISPOSAL/DISPOSITION OF THIS PACKAGE IF NO SHIPPER OR CONSIGNEE NOTIFIES FEDEX ABOUT THIS PACKAGE.
THIS PACKAGE WAS IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE WHEN IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED. THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.
THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE USED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

column168: CN/IC TRAIN CREW SWITCHING IN YARD NOTED VAPOR COMING FROM TOP OF TANK CAR RCRX 1426. ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED AND SHIPPER HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. RESPONSE TEAM CHANGED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. CAR WAS RELEASED TO ITS DESTINATION.

OUR LOADED TRAILER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE TO UNLOAD. D.E.A. WHEN THE PLANT PUT NITROGEN PRESSURE ON THE TRAILER PRODUCT STARTED DRIPPING FROM THE INTERNAL VALVE FLANGE. THE PLANT REDUCED THE NITROGEN PRESSURE AND THE DRIP STOPPED. WE UNLOADED THE TRAILER WITH REDUCED NITROGEN PRESSURE WITH NO PROBLEMS.

DRIVER WAS AT THE LOADING SITE. HE WAS NOT IN ATTENDANCE OF THE TRAILER WHEN LOADING. THIS CAUSED A 1275 GALLON SPILL OF JET A FUEL. THE SPILL WAS IN A CONTAINED AREA. THE DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW LOADING PROCEDURES AND WAS TERMINATED FROM HIS WORK DUTIES.
EMPLOYEE OVERFILLED CARGO TANK. EMPLOYEE PUMPED PART OF THE LOAD BACK INTO THE OIL STOCK TANK. SPILLAGE WAS BIOREMEDIATED PER THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.

AMERICAN HOME PATIENT STAFF MEMBER NOTICED A CONSTANT HISSING SOUND FROM THE CARGO AREA OF THE TRUCK AFTER FILLING THE VEHICLE MOUNTED VESSEL ON THAT TRUCK FROM THE ONSITE BULK TANK.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS OF THE TRUCK, IT WAS DISCOVERED THE BURST DISK OF THE PRESSURE BUILDING LINE WAS LEAKING LIQUID OXYGEN.  MANAGEMENT OF SPRINGFIELD, MO LOCATION OF AMERICAN HOMEPATIENT AS WELL PG WALKER (COMPANY THAT PLUMBED THE TRUCK) WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY, AND IN TURN, PROMPTLY ARRIVED AT THE SCENE.  JIM MILLER FROM PG WALKER WAS ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK AND IDENTIFY THE CAUSE AS LIQUID OZ COMING INTO CONTACT WITH A BURST DISK.  CORRECTIVE ACTION IS P G WALKER WILL REPLUMB THE PRESSURE BUILDING LINE TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, TWO LITER PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE JUG WAS DAMAGED AND THREE WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY TWO LITERS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, BOOTS, AMPHOMAG AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, ONE WET CARTON AND ONE DAMAGED JUG WERE PLACED INTO TWO, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS. THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE THREE UNAFFECTED JUG WERE RECOUPED AND FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ALL FOUR JUGS WERE DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE JUGS WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, CAUSING THE CARTON TO FALL AND THE JUGS TO BE DAMAGED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT RAGS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND FOUR DAMAGED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO A TWENTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, SIX  WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING SIX, SIXTY- FOUR OUNCE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE JUG WAS DAMAGED, FIVE JUGS WERE AFFECTED AND THE REMAINING THIRTY JUGS WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY SIXTY-FOUR OUNCES  OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE JUG WAS DUE TO   BEING CRUSHED BY HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, ABSORBENT PADS AND A BOOM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, ONE DAMAGED JUG, FIVE AFFECTED JUGS AND SIX WET CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO TWO, THIRTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE THIRTY UNAFFECTED JUGS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE PICKING UP A TRAILER AT A STORAGE LOT IN GARY, INDIANA, A DRIVER DISCOVERED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER CONTAINED THE RELEASE USING ABSORBENTS. THE TRAILER WAS SENT TO THE YOUNGSTOWN, IN TERMINAL FOR CLEANUP. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, EIGHT WET CARTONS WERE DISCOVERED, SEVEN CONTAINING SIX HALF GALLON METAL CANS AND ONE CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON METAL CANS IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT SIX, HALF GALLON CANS WERE DAMAGED AND ONE, ONE GALLON CAN WAS DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY FOUR GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM, UNAFFECTED CANS AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AS REQUESTED. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGE FIFTY POUND PLASTIC BAG WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO TABLESPOONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE BAG WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE DURING LOADING. THE CAUSE OF THE PUNCTURE IS UNKNOWN. THE TERMINAL HAZ MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A BROOM AND DUST PAN. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, AND DAMAGED BAG WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. ONE ROADWAY EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO THE RELEASE. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS REQUESTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE CARTON CONTAINING EIGHT, TWELVE OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS DROPPED AND CRUSHED DURING HANDLING AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION,  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED AND SIX WERE AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY TWENTY OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON, DAMAGED BOTTLES AND AFFECTED BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A FORTY--FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, TWELVE WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT EIGHT JUGS WERE DAMAGED AND FORTY WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY 2.5 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE JUGS OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THE JUGS BEING CRUSHED WHEN THE LOAD SHIFTED IN TRANSIT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, TWELVE WET CARTONS, EIGHT DAMAGED JUGS AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO TWO, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS AND TWO, FIFTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS. THE FOUR RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE FORTY UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE RECOUPED AND WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TERMINAL, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS ONE DAMAGED FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAIL. APPROXIMATELY TWO  GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO THE SHRINK-WRAP, THE SKID, AND TO SOIL IN THE TERMINAL YARD. THE  DAMAGE OCCURRED WHEN THE LOAD SHIFTED IN TRANSIT AND THE  JUG WAS PUNCTURED BY THE SKID.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM CONTAINED THE RELEASE IN THE YARD WITH AN ABSORBENT BOOM AND PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES,  ABSORBENTS AND A SHOVEL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS  AND  THE AFFECTED SHRINK-WRAP WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DAMAGED PAIL AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. THE AFFECTED SKID WAS PLACED INTO A PLASTIC HAZMAT BAG. column168: DRIVER STOPPED FOR REFUELING AND FOUND FRONT TRAILER TO BE LEAKING A SUBSTANCE.  THE HAZ MAT SUBCONTRACTOR FOUND THE LEAKING DRUM OF PAINT TO HAVE A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM MIDDLE SECTION.  THE LEAKAGE HAD APPARENTLY BEEN OCCURRING WHILE THE TRUCK WAS TRANSIT AS EVIDENCED BY SPILLAGE ON THE CONNECTING DEVICE BETWEEN THE TWO TRAILERS.  ONCE THE DOORS WERE OPENED, PAINT WAS NOTED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE 55 GALLON LEAKING DRUM HAD APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS REMAINING.  THE UNDRIED SPILLAGE WAS WIPED UP WITH RAGS AND ABSORBENT PADS. NR/NH WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF BY THE SUBCONTRACTOR. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN A HEAVY DUTY PLASTIC BAG AND TAKEN TO THE SUBCONTRACTOR'S SHOP PENDING DISPOSAL INSTRUCTIONS.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF PAINT SPILLED ONTO THE PAVED AREA NEAR THE PETRO FUEL ISLAND AND WAS CLEANED BY POWER WASHING.

column168: WEARING PROPER PPE RESPONDED TO A WET PACKAGE IN THE UNLOAD DOOR 12. PACKAGE WAS DRY BUT APPEARED CHEMICALLY STAINED SO I RETURNED TO THE CAGE. UPON OPENING IT I FOUND THAT THE PLASTIC SEAL ON ONE JAR HAD BROKEN AND THE LID WAS LOOSE ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT TO LEAK- OUT THE OTHER 3 WERE UNDAMAGED AND WERE RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  USING THE DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID CHART THE 4TH WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE DMP. DECONTAMINATED PPE AND FILLED OUT THE PAPERWORK.

WE WERE TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF WASTE PRODUCTS FOR ASHLAND DISTRIBUTION COMPANY.  THE LOAD ORIGINATED IN JACKSON, MS. AND DELIVERED IN MEMPHIS, TN. DURING OUR PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OF THE LOAD WE DID NOT DISCOVER ANY LEAKING DRUMS.  WHILE IN ROUTE WE STOPPED IN TILLATOBA, MS. AND DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING OUT OF BACK OF TRAILER.  WE IMMEDIATELY PLACED ABSORBENT PADS TO ABSORB LEAKING PRODUCT AND CALLED AN CALLED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. THE RESPONSE TEAM OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUMS AND ENTIRE LOAD WAS DELIVERED TO DESTINATION.  CLEAN UP AND DECONTAMINATION COMPLETE.

DRIVER ENTER SULFUR UNLOADING AREA WENT TO HOOK UP UNLOADING PIPE WHEN THE SULFUR VALVE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER FAILED.  CAUSING SULFUR TO SPILL OUT INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE FLOW OF SULFUR AND THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS LOST IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  EMPLOYEES OF C F INDUSTRIES CLEANED UP THE SULFUR IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE VALVE WAS PULLED OUT OF THE TRAILER AND WAS FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE.  THE VALVE WAS REPAIRED AND THE TRAILER WAS PUT BACK IN SERVICE.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THREE PALLETS OF 100 POUND BAGS HAD FALLEN. APPARENTLY THE LOAD SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT. MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES REPACKAGED ALL OF THE FREE PRODUCT AND DAMAGED BAGS. THE REPACKAGED PRODUCT AND DAMAGED BAGS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

PLYWOOD WAS PLACED AROUND THE DRUMS TO PROTECT THEM IN TRANSPORT. THE PLYWOOD FELL WHILE THE TRAILER WAS BEING LOADED. THE PERSON LOADING THE TRAILER DID NOT NOTICE THIS AND CONTINUED LOADING THE TRAILER. AS HE WAS PUTTING THE NEXT PIECE OF FREIGHT INTO THE TRAILER, HE PUNCTURED THE DRUM WITH HIS FORKLIFT. HE HAS BEEN RETRAINED ON THE FORKLIFT.

EMPLOYEE OVERFILLED CARGO TANK. EMPLOYEE PUMPED PART OF THE LOAD BACK INTO THE OIL STOCK TANKS. SPILLAGE WAS BIOREMEDIATED PER THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.
EMPLOYEE OVERFILLED CARGO TANK. EMPLOYEE PUMPED PART OF THE LOAD BACK INTO THE OIL STOCK TANKS. SPILLAGE WAS BIOREMEDIATED PER KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.

DURING UNLOADING AT TERMINAL FACILITY, PERSONNEL OBSERVED DAMAGED BOX WITH SIGNS OF OBVIOUS LIQUID LEAKAGE. THE SUBJECT TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND A SPILL CONTRACTOR (SWS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE) WAS DISPATCHED. CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL EQUIPPED WITH LEVEL B PPE ENTERED THE TRAILER AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING BOTTLE AND ASSOCIATED BOXES THAT WERE CONTAMINATED. ADDITIONAL FREIGHT ALSO CONTAMINATED WAS OFFLOADED AND WRAPPED. NO STORM DRAINS, WATERWAYS OR GROUND (SOIL) SURFACES WERE IMPACTED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE HOOKING UP THE TRANSFER HOSE, APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE OUTLET VALVE OF TANK TRAILER. THE PRODUCT SPRAYED ONTO THE DRIVERS PANTS. THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED BY THE SHIPPER TO REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED CLOTHING, SHOWER THOROUGHLY AND DISPOSE OF THE CONTAMINATED CLOTHING. MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NOT REQUESTED. THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: #165 RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK, NATX 30164, AUGUST 17, 2001, SOUTH JERSEY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0810 HOURS, FRIDAY AUGUST 17, 2001, AT PAVONIA YARD IN CAMPDEN, NEW JERSEY, A CONRAIL CONDUCTOR NOTICED PUFFS OF VAPOR AND WETNESS ON TOP OF TANK CAR NATX 75410 CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. THE TANK CAR WAS SAFELY MOVED TO MOTORPIT TO ISOLATE AND FACILITATE REPAIR. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE SHIPPER, GULBRANDSEN EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WAS A #165 RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK. GULBRANDSEN SECURED THE TANK CAR BY REPLACING THE RUPTURED DISK. REACT NOTIFIED AND CLEANED PRODUCT RESIDUE REMAINING ON CAR. CAUSE CODE 441 NARRI=2(5+5+0)x(2+0)=40

(A) TRAIN DERAILED ON MAIN TRACK DUE TO SHIFTED SUBGRADE WITH THIS TANK CAR DERAILING ON ITS SIDE DOWN A 14' EMBANKMENT SHEARING OFF THE VAPOR VALVE WHICH RESULTED IN PRODUCT RELEASE. REMAINING PRODUCT TRANSFERRED TO TANK TRUCKS. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT REMEDIATED. 13 HOUSEHOLDS EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS. (ALSO SEE BNSF INCIDENT #'S 01-0810-01B & C). (B) TRAIN DERAILED ON MAIN TRACK DUE TO SHIFTED SUBGRADE WITH THIS TANK CAR DERAILING ON ITS SIDE DOWN A 14' EMBANKMENT SHEARING OFF THE VAPOR VALVE WHICH RESULTED IN RELEASE OF PRODUCT. REMAINING PRODUCT TRANSFERED TO TANK TRUCKS. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT REMEDIATED. 13 HOUSEHOLDS EVACUATED FOR APPROX. 6 HOURS. TWO CONTRACT EMPLOYEES COMPLAINING OF PHENOL EXPOSURES WERE TREATED & RELEASED WITH NO LOST WORK DAYS. (ALSO SEE BNSF INCIDENT #'S 01-0810-01A &C). (C) TRAIN DERAILED ON MAIN TRACK DUE TO SHIFTED SUBGRADE WITH THIS TANK CAR DERAILING ON ITS SIDE WITH THE MANWAY NOZZLE AT THE 4 O'CLOCK POSITION. PRODUCT RELEASED VIA THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WITH THE COVER/CAP O-RING MISSING. REMAINING PRODUCT TRANSFERED TO TANK TRUCKS. column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 78 EASTBOUND IN BETHLEHEM, PA A TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS INVOLVED IN A VEHICLE ACCIDENT. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT AS A RESULT TWO, FIBERBOARD CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON METAL PAILS WERE DAMAGED.  APPROXIMATELY EIGHT GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS OFFLOADED BY ROADWAY PERSONNEL AT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT AND BROUGHT BACK TO TANNERSVILLE, PA TERMINAL FOR FURTHER CLEANUP.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, BOOTIES, ABSORBENTS, A DUSTPAN AND BROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, TWO WET CARTONS AND EIGHT DAMAGED CANS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS SENT TO A NEARBY HOSPITAL FOR MEDICAL ATTENTION AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAIN THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING ONE, ONE GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE BOTTLE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP, CAUSING THE BOTTLE TO BE CRUSHED.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT TOWELS.  THE DAMAGED PAIL AND CARDBOARD CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED GLOVES TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE HAZMAT TEAM ALSO USED LITMUS PAPER TO TEST FOR THE PRESENCE OF FREE PRODUCT INSIDE THE AFFECTED CARTON BUT NONE WAS DETECTED.  THE PLASTIC JUG  IN THE AFFECTED CARTON WAS REPACKAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY  DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES.  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE PROCEEDING SOUTHWARD, TANK CAR GATX 63671 WAS OBSERVED TO  BE DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  TRAIN WAS STOPPED AND CAP SECURED WITH WRENCH.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAR WAS NOT LEAKING AT MP 467. THE SHIPPER WILL REPLACE THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET WHEN THE CAR IS NEXT LOADED.  NO FIRE, INJURY, OR ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE RESULTED FROM THIS UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

DRIVER HAD APPLIED AIR PRESSURE IN PREPARATION OF UNLOADING PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK INTO THE CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK.  UPON OPENING THE EXTERNAL VALVE PRODUCT BEGAN LEAKING FROM AROUND THE COLLAR THAT SECURES THE EXTERNAL VALVE ASSEMBLE TO THE VALVE HOUSING. DRIVER CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE AND ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE LOCKING COLLAR.  WHEN UNLOADING WAS AGAIN ATTEMPTED THE LEAK WHILE STILL PRESENT WAS SLOWED TO A MANAGEABLE LEVEL.  RATHER THAT ATTEMPT TO DISCONNECT TRANSFER HOSES TO FURTHER TROUBLESHOOT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK, UNLOADING WAS CONTINUED WHILE AT THE SAME TIME CAPTURING THE SMALL LEAK IN A BUCKET.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS LOST, WITH APPROXIMATELY 1/2 OF THIS CONTAINED IN THE BUCKET. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY PLANT PERSONNEL FOR SUBSEQUENT DISPOSAL.  CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE FROM A DEFECTIVE GASKET THAT WAS NOT DETECTED DURING THE PREPPING OF THE CARGO TANK PRIOR TO LOADING.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: THIS REPORT IS ALSO RELATED TO A DOT F5800.1 FILED FOR PACKAGE 1Z81324E6842277424, SHIPPED ON 8/24/01.  WHILE UNLOADING PACKAGES, EMPLOYEES SUSPECTED A LEAK FROM THE PACKAGE ASSOCIATED WITH THE TRACKING NUMBER 1Z81324E6842275819.  THE PACKAGE WAS WET BUT NOT VISIBLY LEAKING. AS A RESULT, THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER ISOLATED THE PACKAGE IN A SECURE AREA, WHERE IT WAS SET ASIDE FOR COMPLETE RESPONSE.  THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED, PLACARDED, OR DESCRIBED ON A SHIPPING PAPER AS CONTAINING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  MOREOVER, NEITHER THE PACKAGE NOR ITS CONTENTS, FOUR ONE-GALLON BOTTLES,  PROVIDED THE RESPONDER WITH ANY INFORMATION INDICATING THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CONSEQUENTLY, AFTER TIGHTENING THE BOTTLES' CAPS, THE RESPONDER REPACKED THE FOUR ONE-GALLON BOTTLES IN A NEW FIBERBOARD BOX FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.  THE PREVIOUSLY WET FIBERBOARD BOX WAS DRY AT THE TIME OF REPACKAGING.  THE RESPONDER PLACED THIS ORIGINAL OUTER PACKAGING WITHIN A HEAVY GAUGE PLASTIC BAG, PENDING WASTE DISPOSAL, AND STORED THE BAG IN A SHADED AREA.

OUR DRIVER WAS DRIVING SOUTH ON MLK.  HE WAS IN THE LEFT LANE TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 30 MPH.  HE NOTICED A BUS ON THE RIGHT SIGNAL TO GET BACK INTO TRAFFIC.  AT APPROXIMATELY 3:15PM, FOR SOME INEXPLICABLE REASON, THE DRIVER OF THE SMALL CAR DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF OUR DRIVER BRAKED SUDDENLY AND VIOLENTLY.  OUR DRIVER REACTED TO THE CAR IN FRONT AND BRAKED HARD.  HE STARTED BACK DOWN MLK.  A MAN IN A TOW TRUCK HONKED HIS HORN POINTING TO THE SIDE OF THE TARR TRUCK AND PEDESTRIANS YELLED TO THE DRIVER THAT THERE WAS A PROBLEM.  THE DRIVER TURNED ONTO N. IVY AWAY FROM THE MAIN TRAFFIC AND THE PUBLIC.  IPA WAS FLOWING OUT THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRUCK AND POOLING ALONG THE CURB.  THE DRIVER AND A WITNESS CREATED A DIKE TO PREVENT IPA FROM RUNNING DOWN THE STREET.  THE WITNESS CALLED 911 AND HAZMAT UNIT #41 ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  THE DRIVER DETERMINED THAT THE E-CHANNEL HAD BEEN RIPPED FROM THE WALL AND A PIECE OF WOOD HAD PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF AN IPA TOTE BIN.  ON THURSDAY MORNING 8/16/01, THE DRIVER GAVE THE GENERAL MANAGER HIS ACCOUNT OF THE EVENTS LEADING UP TO THE SPILL AND THOSE THAT OCCURRED AFTER IT.  IT WAS DISCUSSED IN A SAFETY MEETING WITH ALL PACKAGE DRIVERS AND AT THE SAFETY COMMITTEE MEETING.  AN ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION REPORT WAS FILLED OUT INCLUDING A COMPLETE ANALYSIS OF WHAT HAPPENED, CONTRIBUTING FACTORS AND RECOMMENDATIONS ON WHAT IS NEEDED TO PREVENT IT FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED WITH FREE PRODUCT ON THE LID IN THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF THE PLASTIC DRUM BEING CRUSHED BETWEEN THE TRAILER WALL AND OTHER FREIGHT WITH LOOSENED THE CLOSURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED SUITS, GLOVES AND ABSORBENT RAGS TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE THIRTY GALLON RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED, SIX GALLON FIBER DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE THIRD-QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUMS WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KS WAS CONTACTED TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP.  THE TWO DAMAGED DRUMS, WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM THAT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A TRAILER IN THE TERMINAL YARD.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND USED ABSORBENT BOOMS AND PADS TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT TO THE ASPHALT SURFACE. ADVANCED RESPONSE, INC. OF MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE RESPONDED TO INVESTIGATE THE RELEASE.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THREE FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS WERE RUPTURED.  APPROXIMATELY FIFTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF INTERNAL PRESSURE IN THE DRUMS WHICH CAUSED THE SEAMS OF THE PLASTIC DRUMS TO FAIL. ADVANCED RESPONSE INC USED NEUTRALIZER TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB THE FREE PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER AND ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE.  ADVANCED RESPONSE, INC RECOVERED THE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT AND PLACED IT INTO ONE FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM.  THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT IN THE THREE FAILED PLASTIC DRUMS WAS PLACED INTO TWO FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS. THE THREE FIFTY-GIVE GALLON PLY RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINING FIVE PLASTIC DRUMS IN THE SHIPMENT AND THE ENTIRE LOAD FROM THE TRAILER IS BEING HELD FOR INSPECTION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING ONE WET CARTON, CONTAINING TWO, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT BOTH JUGS WERE LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING THE CARTON TO TIP OVER AND FREE PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE CAPS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, AMPHOMAG AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND ONE WET CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE CAPS ON THE PLASTIC JUGS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE JUGS WERE RECOUPED AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, ONE WET FIBERBOARD BOX IN A SHIPMENT OF TEN, CONTAINING ONE DAMAGED ONE GALLON PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF HEAVY TOP FREIGHT CRUSHING THE BOX AND RUPTURING THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES,GOGGLES, TYVEK SUITES, BOOTIES, AMPHOMAG, ABSORBENT PADS, A BROOM AND A SHOVEL. THE WET CARTON AND DAMAGED PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WERE PLACED INTO A TWENTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE AMPHOMAG WAS PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE REMAINDER OF THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE THREE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS UNDAMAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOORS,  AN ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE TRAILER. TERMINAL PERSONNEL ISOLATED THE TRAILER. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Incompatible Product; Water Damage
column168: AN IMPROPERLY LABELED CONTAINER WAS INADVERTENTLY PLACED BY OUR LIFT TRUCK DRIVER INTO AN AREA WITH MATERIALS DESIGNATED FOR NON-HAZARDOUS SOLIDIFICATION.  THE MIS-LABLED CONTAINER CONTAINED A WATER REACTIVE SUBSTANCE.  WATER WAS PRESENT IN THE SOLIDIFICATION AREA, AND A REACTION OCCURRED WHEN THE MIS-LABELED MATERIAL WAS PLACED THERE.  A RELEASE OF GAS RESULTED, BUT THERE WERE NO FLAMES, INJURIES/FATALITIES, OR PROPERTY DAMAGE.  THE MATERIAL WAS COMPLETELY CONTAINED IN ORDER TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF SITUATION FROM HAPPENING AGAIN WE HAVE MODIFIED OUR COLOR CODING AND LABELING REQUIREMENTS.  WE HAVE ALSO CREATED A NEW POSITION, MAKING ONE PERSON RESPONSIBLE FOR ALL DRUM TRANSFER OPERATIONS.  THIS HANDS ON POSITION WILL REPORT DIRECTLY TO THE SAFETY DIRECTOR AND WILL ENSURE THAT MATERIALS ARE ACCOUNTED FOR AND THAT THEY END UP WHERE INTENDED.

PUC HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR L.M. MASSARO FOUND CARS ON A HOLD TRACK IN YARD WITH A SMALL DRIPPING TYPE LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OF TANK CAR. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND A SPECIALIST WAS FLOWN IN TO THE SITE. HE REMOVED A SMALL AREA OF CONTAMINATED BALLAST AND PLACED A STAINLESS STEEL BUCKET UNDER THE VALVE TO CONTAIN ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE. AS EXTREME AIR TEMPERATURES SUBSIDED, THE LEAKAGE BECAME MINIMAL. THE SHIPPER OBTAINED THE PROPER PAPERWORK TO MOVE CARS TO BE UNLOADED AT THE SUSQUEHANNA PLANT FACILITY. ALL CONTAMINATED BALLAST AND THE PRODUCT CAUGHT IN THE BUCKET WERE REMOVED TO THE SUSQUEHANNA PLANT WHERE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL SERVICES WERE AVAILABLE. CARS WITH THIS COMMODITY ARE NOW CHECKED DAILY, WHILE BEING HELD IN YARD, TO DETERMINE NO LEAKAGE IS PRESENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON AUGUST 29, 2001, CSXT PERSONNEL NOTICED ACFX 73140, A LOADED TANK CAR OF GASOLINE, LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AT THE CSXT AVON, IN YARD. THE LEAK WAS ESTIMATED TO BE APPROXIMATELY ONE DRIP PER SECOND. A CONTAINER WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK AND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED. A CSXT EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO BE 1/4 TURN LOOSE, THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE PACKING TO BE 3/4 TURN LOOSE AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THESE CONDITIONS WERE REPAIRED, THE LEAK STOPPED, AND THE CAR CONTINUED TO DESTINATION.

ON AUGUST 29,, 2001, PERSONNEL IN THE CSXT PARKERSBURG, WV YARD NOTICED GATX 50733, A LOADED TANK CAR OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID, FUMING FROM THE TOP. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE CONSIGNEE, ALONG WITH A CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. THE CONSIGNEE FOUND THE FRANGIBLE DISC BLOWN AND REPLACED THE DISC. THE FUMING STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED WITHOUT INCIDENT.

ETCX630565 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT AVON YARD, CSXT, AVON, INDIANA. CAR WAS ISOLATED, AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED AN AREA NORTH OF THE YARD APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE DEEP, UNKNOWN WIDTH (APPROX. 15 PEOPLE). RESPONSE REVEALED "O" RING AND "A" END PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS EXTENDED FROM UNDER THE RETAINER CAP. THE "O" RING WAS CAUGHT UNDER THE VALVE SEAT, ALLOWING THE VAPOR TO LEAK FROM THE CAR. THE "O" RING WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 INCH TOO LARGE TO FIT UNDER THE CAP; THE RING WAS CUT, AND THEN GLUED AND REPLACED IN THE RETAINING CAP, RE-APPLIED TO THE VALVE STEM. AFTER RE-ASSEMBLY, THE CAR WAS OBSERVED, WITH NO FURTHER LEAKAGE. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION. THE COMPANY WAS INSTRUCTED TO TAKE THE CAR OUT OF SERVICE UPON RECEIPT AT DESTINATION FOR RECERTIFICATION OF THE RELIEF VALVE. NARRI: 5[4+5+0] X [2+4]=270                       CAUSE CODE: 413,416

column168: DEFECTIVE "O" RINGS ON SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, UTLX 900873, AUGUST 2, 2001 SOUTH JERSEY DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 0745 HOURS, THURSDAY, AUGUST 2, 2001, AT STONEY CREEK YARD IN TRAINER, PA , A CONRAIL YARDMASTER HEARD HISSING FROM TANK CAR UTLX 900873 RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED ETHYLENE OXIDE.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE SHIPPER, SUNOCO AND UNION TANK CAR ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND REPLACED THE "O" RINGS ON THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE TANK CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER, SUNOCO FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 THE FEDEX IADR-DCAA TRACTOR/TRAILER SHUTTLE DRIVER POSITIONED HIS VEHICLE TO BACK INTO THE DCAA DOCK AREA. HE NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND THEN DISCONNECTED HIS TRACTOR AND PULLED IT INTO A SAFE LOCATION.  HE THEN WENT TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND OPENED DOORS ONLY TO FIND THAT THE SMOKE WAS TOO HEAVY TO ATTEMPT CONTAINMENT WITH HIS VEHICLE FIRE EXTINGUISHER.  THE WASHINGTON, DC FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND EXTINGUISHED THE TRAILER FIRE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  ACCORDING TO THE DANGEROUS GOODS MANIFEST FORM THAT WAS TAKEN FROM THE TRACTOR, THERE WERE NO DECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS IN THIS TRAILER. I NOTIFIED THE FAA ABOUT THIS INCIDENT, SINCE SOME OF THE FREIGHT ON THIS TRAILER WAS FREIGHT THAT HAD FLOWN TO THE FEDEX IADR RAMP FACILITY AND BECAUSE OF THE POSSIBILITY THAT THIS FIRE COULD HAVE BEEN STARTED BY A HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  FEDEX SAFETY IN THE WASHINGTON, DC AREA IS CONDUCTING AN INVESTIGATION INTO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: DURING THE OFFLOAD OPERATIONS IN PARKERSBURG, W.V. THE CARGO HANDLERS NOTICED A STRONG SMELL AND THEN A DAMP SPOT ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. INNER INSPECTION REVEALED NINE (9) AEROSOL CANS LOADED INSIDE THE BOX. THE PROTECTIVE CAPS HAD COME OFF OF SOME OF THE AEROSOL CANS AND ONE OF THE CANS HAD THE SPRAY NOZZLE ENGAGED, WHICH SPRAYED PAINT ALL OVER THE INNER UNITS. PACKAGE WAS CLEANED AND PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM. THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR DOCUMENTED TO CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS. THE FAA OFFICE IN PITTSBURGH, PA. WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: UNIT #1 WAS EXITING SOUTHBOUND OFF I-380 ONTO WESTBOUND I-80. WHEN #1 ENTERED THE EXIT RAMP THAT LEADS FROM I-380 TO I-80, UNIT #1 ROLLED OVER TOWARDS THE LEFT. THE RAMP IS A CURVE TYPE RAMP AND THE CURVE TIGHTENS AS A VEHICLE GOES FURTHER INTO THE CURVE. #1 WENT ONTO THE LEFT SHOULDER OF THE CURVE WHICH SLOPES AWAY FROM THE ROADWAY. WHEN THE UNIT GOT ONTO THE SHOULDER THE DRIVER TRIED TO BRING THE UNIT BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY BY STEERING TO THE RIGHT WHICH CAUSED THE ENTIRE UNIT TO ROLL OVER TOWARDS THE LEFT. THE REAR PORTION TO THE TRACTORS FRAME RAIL PUSHED UP THROUGH THE BOTTOM PART OF THE BARREL ON THE CARGO TANK, PUNCTURING A 5" HOLE THROUGH THE BARREL. WHEN THE UNIT CAME TO REST, ON ITS RIGHT SIDE NOTHING WAS LEAKING FROM ANY PART OF THE TRAILER OTHER THAN THE HOLE PUNCHED THROUGH BY THE FRAME RAIL. 587 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT PRIOR TO UNIT BEING LIFTED OUT.

THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY AN OVERFILL SITUATION. WHEN THE UNDERGROUND STORAGETANK (UST) OVERFILLED, THE OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICE IN THE UST DROP TUBE ACTIVATED. THE PNEUMATIC PRESSURE CREATED WHEN THE OVERFILL DEVICE ACTIVATED, CAUSED THE DELIVERY ELBOW ON TOP OF THE UST TO COME OFF THE TOP OF THE TANK, RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF PRODUCT.

column168: THE CARGO TANK DRIVER, AS SOON AS HE REALIZED THAT A SPILL OCCURRED, CONTACTED OUR OFFICE VIA COMPANY RADIO, SINCE THE TRUCK WAS EQUIPPED WITH ABSORBENT PADS, HE USED THE PADS TO ABSORB AS MUCH OF THE SPILLED CRUDE OIL AS POSSIBLE. AN OIL ABSORBING CLAY PRODUCT WAS SPREAD ON THE SPILL SITE AND PLACED ALONG THE ROAD EDGE TO ABSORB ANY OIL BEFORE IT COULD RUN INTO THE SOIL OR THE DRAINAGE DITCH ALONG THE ROAD.. PEAT-SORB A PEAT MOSS OIL ABSORBENT WAS SPREAD OVER THE SPILL AND SWEPT BACK AND FORTH WITH PUSH BROOMS TO ABSORB THE CRUDE OIL. THE PEAT-SORB WAS THEN SWEPT UP FOR DISPOSAL. SAND WAS THEN SPREAD ON THE ROAD SURFACE WHERE THE OIL HAD SPILLED PRIOR TO OPENING THE ROAD TO ASSURE PROPER TRACTION. ALTHOUGH THE CARGO TANK WAS ONLY LOADED TO 75% OF IT'S CAPACITY, 50% OF THE LOAD WAS REMOVED AS A PRECAUTION, THE CARGO TANK WAS INSPECTED AT THE SPILL SITE BY A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSPECTOR FROM THE OHIO HIGHWAY PATROL AND NO PROBLEMS WERE FOUND. SINCE IT WAS DARK WHEN THE VEHICLE WAS MOVED IT WAS ONLY TAKEN A SHORT DISTANCE AND PARKED OVERNIGHT. THE FOLLOWING MORNING THE CARGO TANK WAS INSPECTED BY A CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARGO TANK INSPECTOR. SINCE NO PROBLEMS WERE FOUND THE CARGO TANK WAS TAKEN TO OUR MAINTENANCE SHOP AND WAS AGAIN RE-INSPECTED AND NO PROBLEMS WERE FOUND. THIS LEAVES DRIVER ERROR AS THE ONLY REMAINING POSSIBILITY , ALTHOUGH THE ERROR COULD NOT BE IDENTIFIED DURING THE POST ACCIDENT INTERVIEW WITH THE DRIVER, WE FEEL THAT THE DRIVER MUST HAVE LEFT A VALVE OPEN OR PARTIALLY OPEN BETWEEN COMPARTMENTS AFTER LOADING THE CRUDE OIL AT THE OIL  WELL PRODUCTION SITE, AS THE TRUCK WENT UP HILLS, THE LOAD WOULD SHIFT TO THE REAR COMPARTMENT CAUSING A PRESSURE INCREASE WHICH CAUSED SMALL AMOUNTS OF OIL TO BE RELEASED FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. THE OIL CONTINUED TO BUILD UP IN THE THE TROUGH ON TOP OF THE CARGO TANK UNTIL THE QUANTITY WAS ENOUGH TO RUN OUT THE TROUGH'S DRAIN TUBE. WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED THE CARGO TANK WAS ON A INCLINE AT A STOP SIGN, THE DRIVER WAS RE-TRAINED ON THE PROPER USE OF THIS CARGO TANK. PRIOR TO THE COMPANY BEING NOTIFIED BY OUR DRIVER THE ALEXANDRIA POLICE DEPARTMENT HAD ALREADY CONTACTED THE THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE. SECTION OF THE OHIO E.P.A., THE LICKING COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY, THE OHIO HIGHWAY PATROL AND THE ALEXANDRIA - ST. ALBANS FIRE DEPARTMENT. AFTER THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP EMPLOYEES CHECKED THE SITE TO MAKE SURE THAT THE ROAD HAD NOT BECOME SLICK DURING THE MORNING AND AFTERNOON OF SEPTEMBER 1ST, 2ND AND 3RD, THE SITE WAS CHECKED AGAIN AROUND NOON ON SEPTEMBER 4TH AND AFTER THE NEXT RAIN, DUE TO CONCERN FOR PUBLIC SAFETY. DURING THE MORNING OF SEPTEMBER 4TH I CONTACTED MR. MIKE DALTON OF THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE SECTION OF THE OHIO E.P.A. AND MR. JEFF WALKER OF THE LICKING COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY TO MAKE SURE THEY WERE SATISFIED WITH OUR RESPONSE AND CLEAN UP. BOTH OF THESE INDIVIDUALS WERE AT THE SPILL SITE AND I COMMEND THEM FOR THEIR HELP AND COOPERATION, BOXES OF PEAT-SO

THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORT OPERATION. THIS PACKAGE WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED CAUSING THE INTERNAL GLASS CONTAINER TO FAIL. THE SHIPMENT WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM UNTIL THE SHIPPER COULD BE CONTACTED FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET REGARDING THE COMMODITY. AFTER RECEIVING THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET, WHICH STATED THIS TO BE AMYL ACETATE, I NOTIFIED DON STIGER OF THE PDX/CASFU TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. AFTER HIS INVESTIGATION, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR THE CUSTOMER TO PICK UP THE SHIPMENT.

THE KCS EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 0130 HOURS. THE CONTRACTOR TURNED THE VALVE KNOB 1/4 TURN TO THE RIGHT SHUTTING THE LEAK DOWN COMPLETELY. AFTER WAITING 30 MINUTES, THE CONTRACTOR CHECKED THE CAR AGAIN. THE TANK CAR HAD APPROXIMATELY 20 LBS. PRESSURE ACCORDING TO THE GAUGE. AFTER ANOTHER 20 MINUTES, THE CAR WAS CHECKED AGAIN. EVERYTHING APPEARED FINE, THE ARGON FOG SEEMED TO BE DISSIPATING, AND THE CAR WAS READY TO BE FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION. NARRI: = 5[5+1+0] X [2+0] = 60                                CODE:= 276

column168: ON FRIDAY AUGUST 24, 2001 (6:30 A.M.) AT THE INTERSECTION OF INTERSTATE 78 AND ROUTE 525 (LIBERTY CONNER ROAD) IN SUMMERSET, NJ, AN ORICA APEX GOLD BULK TRUCK TURNED OVER ON ITS SIDE.  THE DRIVER EXITED THE INTERSTATE AND APPLIED THE JAKE BRAKE, DOWN SHIFTED ONCE ON THE EXIT RAMP.  HE PROCEEDED THROUGH A GREEN LIGHT.  HE WAS MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN TO CROSS THE BRIDGE WHEN HE FELT THE TRUCK SLOWLY TURN OVER ON THE PASSENGER SIDE.  THE VEHICLE IS IMPOUNDED BY THE NJ STATE PATROL FOR COMPLETE SAFETY REVIEW. MAINTENANCE ON THE VEHICLE IS LIMITED AS THIS WAS A 2000 MACK WITH 7500 MILES.  THE EMPLOYEE RECEIVED 3 STITCHES TO HIS HEAD AND RELEASED FROM HOSPITAL.  A SMALL FIRE STARTED AROUND THE TURBO WHICH WAS EXTINGUISHED QUICKLY BY THE EMPLOYEE AND BY LOCAL BYSTANDERS.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS LIMITED TO ANTI-FREEZE AND WATER SOLUTION MIXTURE.  ON SITE CLEAN UP WAS REVIEWED BY DEP STATE OF NJ.  THE ACCIDENT IS CURRENTLY UNDER INVESTIGATION BY ORICA AND NJ STATE PATROL.  AT THIS TIME WE ARE REVIEWING ALL DOCUMENTS AND PICTURES.  CAUSES WILL BE ANNOUNCED PENDING THE OUT COME OF THE NJ STATE PATROL SAFETY REVIEW AND ORICA DESIGN REVIEW.  ORICA HAS REQUESTED FROM THE DENVER TECHNICAL CENTER AND TREAD CORPORATION OF VIRGINIA FOR A COMPLETE DESIGN REVIEW.  ORICA HAS REQUESTED A SHE ALERT BE ISSUED UNTIL WE RESOLVE THIS MATTER.  SHE ALERT ISSUED ON SEPTEMBER 04, 2001.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER OF BT309 WAS OPERATING A D.C. GUELICH EXPLOSIVE CO. STRAIT TRUCK CARING 30,000 # OF AMMONIUM NITRATE AND 2,400 # OF FUEL OIL, NORTH BOUND ON SR2023. BT309 SUFFERED A SUSPENSION RELATED FAILURE AT THE RIGHT REAR AXLE THAT DEPOSITED TWO SECTION OF BROKEN U BOLT ONTO THE HIGHWAY, LEAVING PAVEMENT ABRASIONS IN THE ASPHALT SURFACE ALONG THE NORTH BOUND LANE. THE BROKEN U BOLT SECTIONS WERE DISCOVERED ALONG THE NORTH BOUND BERM OF SR2023, APPROXIMATELY 287 FEET PRIOR TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT. BT309'S RIGHT REAR TIRES BEGAN TO SEIZE AS RESULT OF THE SUSPENSION FAILURE, BEING PRESSED AGAINST THE UNDERCARRIAGE BY THE WEIGHT OF THE LOAD. BT309 WENT OUT OF THE DRIVER'S CONTROL, TRAVELING UNTO THE NORTHBOUND BERM OF SR2023 WHERE IT COLLIDED WITH THE GUARDRAILING. BT309 U-BOLT PLATE, DESIGNED TO SECURE THE LEAF SPRING SUSPENSION TO THE VEHICLE WAS FOUND AT THE ONSET OF THE SKID MARKS LEFT BY BT309'S RIGHT REAR TIRES. IN RELATIONS, BT309 BROKEN U-BOLT SECTIONS WERE LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 76 FEET PRIOR TO THE SKID MARKS LEFT BY BT309'S RIGHT REAR WHEELS. NONE OF BT309'S OTHER WHEELS WERE EFFECTED BY THE SUSPENSION FAILURE TO THE POINT OF LOCK UP. BT309 CONTINUED NORTH ALONG THE BERM WHERE IT COLLAPSED THE GUARDRAILING OF SR2023. BT309 PASSED THROUGH THE GUARDRAILING AND TRAVELED DOWN A STEEP EMBANKMENT, COMING TO REST ON ITS ROOF UPON A SECTION OF T-598, KNOWN  AS LOG CABIN ROAD.

column168: THE NURSE TANK ROLLOVER OCCURRED AS AN EMPLOYEE WAS PULLING THE TANK AROUND THE CORNER WHEN A BOLT THAT HOLDS THE ROCKING BOLSTER PIN IN PLACE BROKE. THIS ALLOWED THE TANK TO SEPARATE FROM THE TURNING AXLE AND ROLLOVER.  WHEN THE TANK OVERTURNED THE TANK VALVE ROLL CAGE COLLAPSED ONTO THE TANK LOADOUT VALVE CAUSING THE VALVE TO BREAK.  THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE IN THE LOWER PART OF THE LOADOUT VALVE ACTIVATED IMMEDIATELY TO STOP THE FLOW OF MOST OF THE PRODUCT; HOWEVER, THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE DID NOT SEAL COMPLETELY.  AS A RESULT THE POOR SEALING EXCESS FLOW VALVE, NH3 WAS SLOWLY RELEASING FROM THE BROKEN VALVE.  THE TANK WAS REMOVED TO A REMOTE LOCATION TO LET THE PRESSURE BLEED OFF ON ITS OWN THROUGH THE SEEPING EXCESS FLOW VALVE.  COMPANY EMPLOYEES MONITORED THE TANK UNTIL THE TANK HAD RELEASED ALL OF ITS CONTENTS.  IT TOOK 48HRS FOR THE TANK TO EMPTY.

THEY AND THE DRIVER TOOK PHOTOS.  THE CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL PUT THE OVERPACK BACK ON THE CARRIER'S TRUCK.  DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO MARK AND LABEL THE DRUM, THEN CONTINUE ON WITH HIS ASSIGNED WORK.

column168: DURING UNLOADING AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM ITS BOTTOM.  INSPECTION REVEALED A SMALL CRACK IN THE BOTTOM HEAD.  THE SPILLAGE WAS WIPED UP AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM TO AWAIT THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.

SHIPMENT WAS PICKED UP AT THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY AND TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY TO BE PUT OUT FOR DELIVERY.  DURING UNLOADING AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY SOME SPILLAGE WAS OBSERVED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  DAMAGE TO A BAG WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE OCCURRED WHEN THE SHIPPER LOADED THE MATERIAL AGAINST A DAMAGED PORTION OF THE TRAILER'S SCUFF RAIL.  THE DAMAGED BAG WAS SECURED AND CONTINUED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  ON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE THERE WERE NUMEROUS LEAKING BAGS ON FOUR OF THE TEN PALLETS IN THE SHIPMENT.  THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT.  CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN SPOKE WITH A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE CONSIGNEE WHO INDICATED THAT AN ONGOING PROBLEM EXISTS.  THEY (THE CONSIGNEE) HAVE SPOKEN WITH THE SHIPPER ABOUT THEIR PACKAGING ON PREVIOUS OCCASIONS.  THE CONSIGNEE'S REPRESENTATIVE HAS EXPLAINED TO THE SHIPPER THAT THE PACKAGING IS NOT STANDING UP UNDER NORMAL TRANSIT CONDITIONS.  CONSIGNEE ASSISTED THE DRIVER IN PREPARING THE SHIPMENT FOR RETURN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY.  WHEN COMPLETED, THE DRIVER RETURNED DIRECTLY, MAKING NO ADDITIONAL DELIVERIES OR PICK UPS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TAKEN TO ANOTHER FACILITY FOR REPACKAGING.

AT TIME OF DELIVERY ONE PAIL WAS LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM. IT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN WEDGED IN BETWEEN THE TRAILER WALL AND A PALLET. DRIVER USED MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO CLEAN UP THE FLOOR. HE DISPOSED OF THEM IN THE CONSIGNEE'S DISPOSAL SYSTEM.

ONE DRUM OF A 21 DRUM SHIPMENT OF H/M WAS SECURED BY ITSELF AT THE TAIL OF THE CARRIER'S TRAILER. DURING DELIVERY OF A DIFFERENT SHIPMENT AT INTERMEDIATE STOP. THE SINGLE DRUM WAS STRUCK BY A FORK LIFT AND PUNCTURED. CARRIER'S DRIVER AND THE FACILITY'S FORK LIFT OPERATOR TURNED THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE, NOT UNTIL APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF THE H/M HAD ESCAPED TO THE GROUND. CONFLICTING ACCOUNTS OF THE NATURE AND SEQUENCE OF EVENTS WERE INITIALLY RECEIVED. SINCE THE RESPONSIBILITY WAS UNCLEAR AT THAT TIME, THE CARRIER ACTED TO RETAIN A SPILL CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP. THE DRUM WAS SECURED AND TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S NEARBY FACILITY. IT WAS ULTIMATELY DETERMINED THAT THE DRUM  HAD IN FACT BEEN FORKED AT THE INCIDENT SITE BY AN EMPLOYEE OF THAT COMPANY.

DRIVER IS ON A ROAD TRIP WITH SEVERAL ENROUTE STOPS. AT THE LAST STOP BEFORE REACHING THE CARRIER'S FACILITY HE ENCOUNTERED A STRONG ODOR WHEN HE ENTERED THE TRAILER. HE INVESTIGATED AND FOUND ONE DRUM WITH A LOOSE HEAD CLAMP RING. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE RING HAD FRACTURED AND BROKEN AT A POINT ABOUT AN INCH FROM THE BOLT FLANGE. HE IS ABOUT TWELVE MILES FROM THE CARRIER'S FACILITY. HE BELIEVES THAT HE CAN MAKE IT WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN INSTRUCTED HIM ON HOW TO SECURE THE PACKAGE FROM FURTHER  LEAKAGE, THEN INSTRUCTED HIM TO CONTINUE TO THE FACILITY. THE TECHNICIAN CONTACTED THE FACILITY AND ADVISED THEM THAT A CONTRACTOR WOULD BE SENT TO SITE TO COMPLETE MITIGATION OF THE INCIDENT. CONTRACTOR ONSITE REPORTED THAT THE LID GASKET WAS THE PROBLEM AND THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE. AT HAZMAT'S REQUEST THE CONTRACTOR REPLACED THE LID, GASKET AND RING ASSEMBLY AND DRUM WAS PUT WITH THE ORDER TO COMPLETE THE SHIPMENT.

PAILS OF H/M STACKED IN THE TRAILER ARRIVED AT THE CARRIER'S DELIVERING FACILITY; ONE PAIL HAD FALLEN TO THE FLOOR AND OPENED. ABOUT TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN SPILLED BUT WAS CONTAINED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. AFTER UNLOADING, THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE AND SENT TO A WASHOUT FACILITY.

column168: TRUCK WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON I90 IN WARREN, MA. WITH TWO PALLETS OF CHEMICALS IN ROUTE TO BROADBROOK, CT. TO LEAVE PRODUCT FOR RETURN TO CHEMICAL DISTRIBUTOR.  THE PALLETS WERE CAPPED AND WRAPPED WITH SHRINK WRAP WHEN THEY LEFT MARLBORO, MA. IN TRANSIT THE REAR PALLET'S COVER LIFTED FROM THE WIND AND CAUSED THE TOP SEALED BOX (5GL CASE) TO BECOME EXPOSED AND THE CONTAINER FELL OFF THE PALLET AND ONTO THE INTERSTATE.  THE IMPACT CAUSED THE SEALED BOX AND JUGS TO BREAK AND CROSS TWO LANES OF HIGHWAY.  THE CLEANUP WAS MINIMAL BECAUSE MOST OF THE PRODUCT DRIED OR EVAPORATED QUICKLY.  THE PRODUCT REMAINING WAS ABSORBED WITH SPEEDY-DRI AND SWEPT UP BY THE D.O.T. AGENT.  THE MASS D.E.P. AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE NUMBER WERE CALLED IMMEDIATELY.  ABOUT ONE AND ONE HALF-GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SWEPT INTO A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  ENSTRAT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES IN MARLBORO, MA. DID ALL REPORTS AND DRUM DISPOSAL FOR THE MASS D.E.P. PROPER LOADING AND SECURING THE LOAD PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH MANAGER AT MARLBORO, MA.

column168: OUR VEHICLE AND DRIVER WERE INVOLVED IN THE OVERFILL OF A 2,000 GALLON UNDERGROUND FUEL OIL TANK AT THE CLAYTON H. LANDIS COMPANY, 467 MEETINGHOUSE ROAD, SOUTHERTON, PA, ON AUGUST 10, 2001, AT APPROXIMATELY 8:30 AM. THE TANK WAS OVERFILLED DUE TO LACK OF SUPERVISION BY A LANDIS EMPLOYEE DURING THE PUMPING PROCESS. THERE IS NO VENT ALARM ON THE VENT PIPE, AND THEREFORE AN EXTRA PERSON IS REQUIRED TO SUPERVISE THE FILLING OF THE TANK AND NOTIFY THE DRIVER WHEN THE TANK IS NEARING THE FULL STAGE. THE LANDIS EMPLOYEE DID SUPERVISE THE MEASUREMENT OF THE TANK BEFORE IT WAS FILLED AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER ON THE AMOUNT TO PUT IN THE TANK, BUT THEN LEFT THE DRIVER ON HIS OWN. THE TANK WAS FILLED BEYOND CAPACITY, EVEN THOUGH THE DRIVER PUT IN ONLY THE AMOUNT SPECIFIED, AND APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS OF #2 HEATING OIL WAS SPILLED ON THE CUSTOMER'S LAWN. (AS OF THIS DATE, NO DETERMINATION HAS BEEN MADE ON THE ACTUAL CAUSE OF THE SPILL.)  ABSORBENT MATERIALS (BOOMS AND OIL DRY) WERE INSTALLED BY HEAVENER SUPPLY EMPLOYEES TO PREVENT THE PRODUCT FROM LEAVING THE PROPERTY. THE SITE WAS REMEDIATED BY THE LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP, 77 WELLS ROAD, POTTSTOWN, PA. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL, APPROXIMATELY 251 TONS, WAS TRANSPORTED TO R3 TECHNOLOGIES, 7 STEEL ROAD, MORRISVILLE, PA FOR DISPOSAL. ALL OF THE SPILLAGE WAS CONFINED TO THE CUSTOMER'S PROPERTY, AND NO PRODUCT ENTERED ANY WATERWAY OR DRAINAGE SYSTEM. THERE WAS NO CONTACT WITH THE FUEL OIL BY ANYONE, AND NO ONE WAS INJURED BY THE FUEL OIL SPILL OR THE CLEAN UP. TO PREVENT FUTURE SPILLAGE AND CONTAMINATION, NO DELIVERIES WILL BE MADE UNLESS A LANDIS OR HEAVENER EMPLOYEE ARE ON SITE TO ASSIST IN THE PUMPING/ FILLING PROCESS. LANDIS COMPANY HAS BEEN NOTIFIED IN WRITING OF THE NEW PROCEDURE, AND NOTATIONS HAVE BEEN ADDED TO THE SHIPPING MANIFEST TO INSTRUCT DRIVERS OF THE NEW PROCEDURE.

column168: 41 R RECEIVING TANK AT DELIVERY LOCATION WAS UNHOOKED FROM FILL AND VENT LINES LEADING OUTSIDE OF THE HOME. IX- THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT A RESIDENCE. THE CUSTOMER PURCHASE OIL FROM OUR COMPANY THROUGH OUR AUTO-FILL PROGRAM. THE CUSTOMER ASKED UNHOOK THEIR TANK LOCATED IN THE BASEMENT OF THE HOME FROM THE FILL, VENT AND SUPPLY LINES LEADING TO THE FURNACE. THIS WAS DUE TO THEIR NEED TO MOVE THE TANK IN ORDER FOR A WATER LEAKAGE PROBLEM TO BE CORRECTED. OUR SERVICE PERSONNEL REMOVED THE OIL AND UNHOOKED THE TANK AS THE CUSTOMER REQUESTED. UNFORTUNATELY AND DUE TO HUMAN ERROR THE CUSTOMER WAS NOT REMOVED FROM THE AUTO-FILL PROGRAM AS PART OF WHAT WOULD HAVE BEEN NORMAL PROCEDURE. DURING THIS TIME PERIOD WE WERE PERFORMING OUR SUMMER FILLS AND A BATCH OF TICKETS WERE GENERATED ONE OF WHICH WAS THIS DELIVERY THE DRIVER WENT TO THE HOME AND BEGAN FILLING THE TANK. HE DID NOT KNOW OR REALIZE THE TANK HAD BEEN TEMPORALLY UNHOOKED FROM THE LINE LEADING OUTSIDE THE HOME. A TOTAL OF 108 GALLONS OF OIL WAS PUMPED FROM THE TRUCK AND SPILLED. OUR COMPANY RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO BEGIN THE CLEAN UP. WE CONTINUED TO WORK DILIGENTLY IN CONJUNCTION WITH INSURANCE AND REMEDIATION CONTRACTORS TO CONTINUE THE CLEAN UP PROCESS. CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN WERE TO REITERATE CURRENT OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES IN OUR CUSTOMER SERVICE, MAINTENANCE AND DELIVERY DEPARTMENTS. ALSO NEW PROCEDURES WERE ALSO ADDED WITH RESPECT TO ALL OF THE ABOVE.

column168: ON 8/15/01, INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR JAMES HAYES) WAS DISPATCHED TO PICK UP A LOAD OF FUEL OIL AT 12:00 A.M. AT A LOCATION 2 MILES WEST AND NORTH OF HIGHWAY 82 NEAR GAINESVILLE, TEXAS. UPON ARRIVAL, OF THE PICK UP LOCATION, JAMES HAYES LOADED 5400 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL ON TRAILER F-23 WITH A SHORT FORM BILL OF LADING 6S695/6P695 WITH A SHIPPER'S BILL OF LADING NO. 0108-209. AS JAMES LEFT THE PICK UP LOCATION AT APPROXIMATELY 1:45 A.M., HE PROCEEDED DOWN THE SERVICE ROAD ALONG I-35E IN ORDER TO ENTER ONTO I-35E.  PRIOR TO THE ENTRANCE RAMP, THERE WAS AN EXIT RAMP IN WHICH JAMES BRAKED TO ENSURE TRAFFIC WAS NOT EXITING I-35.  AT THE TIME JAMES WAS BRAKING THE FUEL OIL IN TRAILER F-23 SHIFTED FORWARD AND ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL TO SPILL OUT OF THE DOME LID.  JAMES NOTICED THE FUEL OIL RUNNING SOWN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND LEAVING A TRAILER ON THE SERVICE ROAD.  AT THIS TIME JAMES HAYES STOPPED AND NOTIFIED THE DISPATCHER ON CALL, WHO IN TURN CALLING TOM LASSANSKE.  TOM LASSANSKE DISPATCHED HULCHER SERVICES INCORPORATED TO RESPOND AND CLEAN UP THE MATERIAL THAT WAS SPILLED. HULCHER SERVICES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT A APPROXIMATELY 5:00 A.M. AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY AND GAINESVILLE, TEXAS FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ASSIST IN THE BARRICADING AND BLOCKING OF THE EXIT RAMP AND SERVICE ROAD.  THE FUEL OIL WAS CLEANED FROM THE TRAILER F-23 AND WAS PRESSURE WASHED FROM THE SERVICE ROAD AND VACUUMED UP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 A.M., HULCHER SERVICES INCORPORATED NOTIFIED COAL CITY COB COMPANY THAT ALL MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP TO THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION'S SATISFACTION AND TRAILER F-23 WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED TO THE FINAL DESTINATION.

column168: 1.THE MAUMEE EXPRESS DRIVER WAS DOING HIS PRE TRIP INSPECTION BEFORE LEAVING THE TRUCK STOP LOCATED AT I-70 EXIT 79 WHEN HE NOTICED A SMALL DRIP COMING FROM THE BOTTOM SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND ACCUMULATING ON THE ASPHALT. 2.THE DRIVER APPLIED ABSORBENTS AROUND THE DRIP AREA TO CONTAIN THE SPILL 3.THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS OFFICE. 4. THE MAUMEE EXPRESS TRUCK WAS LOCATED AT THE REAR OF THE TRUCK STOP PARKING LOT. 5.THE SPILL RESPONSE WAS INITATED BY CONTACTING CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL IN CINCINNATI WHO DISPATCHED A CREW THEIR CLEVELAND OFFICE TO RESPOND. 6. AT APPROX 1PM EST NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) (REPORT #575764) AND THE OHIO STATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMMISSION (SERC) (REPORT#0108-49-2949) OF THE RELEASE. 7. THE CLEAN HARBOR RESPONSE CREW ARRIVES ON SCENE AND INITIATES RESPONSE BY MONITORING AIR QUALITY INSIDE OF THE VAN TRAILER. AFTER AIR MONITORING THE RESPONSE CREW BEGINS RELOCATING CONTAINERS TO FIND THE LEAKING 55 GAL DRUM WHICH IS LOCATED AT THE MIDDLE OF THE MAUMEE EXPRESS VAN TRAILER. THE 55 GAL DRUM CONTAINED WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. WITH THE MAIN CONSTITUENTS BEING ACETONE AND ETHYLENE GLYCOL. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TRANSFERRED INTO AN 85 GAL OVER PACK CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE SPILLED MATERIAL INCLUDING THE ABSORBENT USED FOR THE SPILL CLEANUP. THE OVER PACK DRUM WAS THEN TRANSPORTED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO POLLUTION CONTROL INDUSTRIES. A COPY OF CLEAN HARBORS SPILL REPORT IS ATTACHED. 8. AFTER THE DRUM WAS WEIGHTED AT POLLUTION CONTROL INDUSTRIES THE RELEASE WAS DETERMINED TO BE 42 POUNDS. IN ADDITION TO THE 42 POUNDS RELEASED 30 POUNDS OF ABSORBENT WAS USED FOR THE CLEAN UP.
NOZZLE SLIPPED OUT OF DRIVER'S HAND CAUSING OUTAGE WHICH WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

DESCRIPTION OF INCIDENT: SKYCAP EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED THREE 1-QT. BOTTLES OF 100% EUCALYPTUS OIL, TWO BROKEN. WHILE OFFLOADING FLT. 922 INTO CUSTOMS 2 OF 3 BOTTLES BROKE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE BAG. MDAD HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND BAGGED THE CONTENTS OF THE BAGGAGE. THE PASSENGER WAS TRAVELING WITH THE PRODUCT TO USE AT HOME AND WAS NOT AWARE OF HAZARDOUS PROPERTIES ASSOCIATED WITH IT. THERE WERE NO VISIBLE TRIGGERS AT CHECK IN.  DISCOVERED AT TRANSFER. THE PASSENGER WAS EDUCATED ON FAA REGULATIONS REGARDING TRAVELING WITH DANGEROUS GOODS AND GIVEN THE "THESE FLY..." PAMPHLET. PASSENGER WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE. PHOTOS WERE TAKEN FOR THE FAA INVESTIGATION. THE CONTENTS AND REMAINING BOTTLE WILL BE HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION.

column168: NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 11:15 OF THE RELEASE OF A SUSPECTED HAZMAT RELEASE FROM PASSENGER BAGGAGE FOUND DURING THE LOADING PROCESS ASSOCIATED WITH AA1517 DFW-SLC ON GATE C2 AT DFW AIRPORT. THE BAGGAGE BELONGED TO PASSENGER ZACKARY STEVEN LUDLOW WHO ORIGINATED IN RIBEIRAO PRETO, BRAZIL AND WAS IN-TRANSIT AT DFW. OBSERVED THE SPILLED PRODUCT, "PERMA-KILL" 13.3 % PERMETHRIN SOLUTION MANUFACTURED BY COULSTON PRODUCTS- USED TO REPEL INSECTS WHEN APPLIED AS A SOLUTION TO CLOTHING OR IN PERIMETER AREAS. THE UNBROKEN PLASTIC 8 OZ BOTTLE WAS MARKED AS FLAMMABLE AND CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 1OZ. OF THE ORIGINAL CONTENTS. MATERIAL WAS SUSPECTED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE OPENING/ CAP. CLOTHING AND PERSONAL EFFECTS IN THE SUITCASE WERE SATURATED WITH LIQUID. NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ON THE AIRCRAFT; RATHER, IT WAS DISCOVERED WHILE THE BAGGAGE WAS ON A CONVEYOR PRIOR TO LOADING. MSDS INFORMATION CLASSIFIED THE SUBSTANCE AS UN1993 CLASS 3 FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. AFTER INITIAL PUSHBACK OF THE AIRCRAFT, THE CAPTAIN ELECTED TO RETURN TO THE GATE REQUESTING A PRECAUTIONARY INSPECTION. SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION VERIFIED THAT THE AIRCRAFT WAS SUITABLE FOR RE-RELEASE. THE PASSENGER WAS INTERVIEWED AND EDUCATED ABOUT DG REGULATIONS AND WAS BOOKED FOR A LATER SLC FLIGHT. BAGGAGE AND THE PRODUCT WERE CONFISCATED AND THE INCIDENT REPORTED TO THE FAA. EMPLOYEES WERE PROVIDED MSDS INFORMATION WHICH SPECIFIED THAT ANY SKIN AREAS IN CONTACT WITH THE LIQUID SHOULD BE WASHED WITH SOAP AND WATER AS A PRECAUTION.

column168: FILE:2148 P&D, SHIPPER; BRAVA LLC. AWB# MIA 2077098310 MIA. ON 8/8/2001 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATORS TAMAR RAMIREZ AND CHARLES JONES DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BLACK PLASTIC CASE THAT HAD VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE COMING FROM A SEAM ON THIS CASE. THEY REMOVED THIS FORM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THIS WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN: 1X16 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH PLASTIC FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE, "ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL 70%". THIS BOTTLE WAS SPLIT NEAR THE BOTTOM CAUSING THIS TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 5-1 OUNCE. THERE WERE OTHER MISCELLANEOUS NON REGULATED ITEMS IN THIS CASE. THIS DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THEY BAGGED THE LEAKING ITEM AND THEN REPLACED THE ITEMS INTO THE CASE, PLACED THE CASE INTO A FIBERBOARD BOX. THEY PLACED THE FIBERBOARD BOX INTO THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS DID NOT HAVE ANY MARKINGS, LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE  CONTENTS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE SPILL WAS CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED. THERE WERE 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE SPILL THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IS WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED IN THESE EMPLOYEES, NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE AT ILN. CLEAR OF SCENE 0205

THIS REPORT IS ALSO RELATED TO A DOT F5800.1 FILED FOR PACKAGE 1Z 813 24E 68 4227 5819, SHIPPED ON 8/23/01. THIS SECOND PACKAGE , IZ 813 24E 68 4227 7427, WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE TUB ON 8/24 AFTER THE EVENTS REPORTED IN RELATION TO 1Z 813 24E 68 4227 5819. SIMILARLY, THIS SECOND PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED LABELED, PLACARDED, OR DESCRIBED ON SHIPPING PAPER AS CONTAINING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND NEITHER THE PACKAGE NOR ITS CONTENTS PROVIDED ANY INFORMATION INDICATING THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. HAVING WITNESSED THE HEAT REACTION OF THE FIRST PACKAGE, THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS PROCESSING THE SECOND SHIPMENT (1Z 813 24E 68 4227 7424) ABSORBED THE LIQUID IN A CLAY BASED ABSORBENT SUCH THAT THERE WAS NO FREE LIQUID. THE ABSORBENT AND DRIED FIBERBOARD WERE PLACED IN A HEAVY GAUGE PLASTIC BAG, TAPED SHUT, AND MONITORED BY THESE EMPLOYEES. IN A SHORT TIME, THIS BAG INFLATED WITH SMOKE. THE EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED BY DOUSING THE BAG AND ITS CONTENTS WITH WATER. A PRIVATE OUTSIDE RESPONSE AGENCY WAS CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE IN SAFELY SECURING THE  REMNANTS OF BOTH PACKAGES.1Z 813 24E 68 4227 7424 AND 1Z 813 24E 68 4227 5819. FURTHER, AS A SAFETY PRECAUTION, TWO ADDITIONAL PACKAGES OF THE SAME MATERIAL (TRACKING NUMBERS UNKNOWN) WERE REMOVED FROM THE OPERATION AND PROCESSED BY THE OUTSIDE RESPONDER.

THE SPILL AREA ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR WAS CLEANED AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO FORWARD TO DESTINATION. CORRECTIVE AND PREVENTATIVE ACTIONS WERE DISCUSSED WITH MR. DUNN

column168: FILE: 2152 F&D, SHIPPER: NEW YORK LIFE INS 01V14, AWB # 5182084423 SYR. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS CHRISTI KIRKER AND CECELIA HICKEY DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE LID, WHICH RESULTED IN THE LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 6 OUNCES.  THIS DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER.  THERE WAS ATTENTION WAS NEEDED NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED IN THIS EMPLOYEE, NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED. THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE AT ILN. CLEAR OF SCENE 0147.

column168: AIR CARGO WAS DROPPED OFF AT THE CARGO FACILITY. STEVE MUELLER CALLED ME AND INFORMED ME THAT HE HAD DISCOVERED A FOUL SMELL COMING FROM A BOX. HE OPENED THE BOX AND DISCOVERED A BOX CONTAINING FORD MOTOR CRAFT FUEL INJECTOR CLEANER. INSIDE THE BOX WERE THREE SMALLER BOXES WITH 12 8-OUNCE BOTTLES PER BOX. ONE BOX HAD LEAKED A LITTLE FLUID OUT OF ONE OF THE BOTTLES INSIDE THE SMALLER BOXES. WE DID NOT SEE ANY DAMAGE TO THE OUTER CONTAINER. THE LEAK DID NOT SEEM TO BE CAUSED FROM MISHANDLING. THE SHIPPER WAS AER MANUFACTURING. THE BOX WAS SHIPPED TO ACTION EXPRESS AND WAS TO BE DELIVERED TO SWELL FORD IN ODESSA TX.

ALAN POULIN (RAMP SUPERVISOR) CONTACTED ME TO HEAD TO T-POINT FOR AN IRREGULARITY. ALBERT BARBOSA AND TOM FLODIN (RAMP AGENTS) NOTICED ONE OF TWO CONTAINERS SHIPPED AS BAGGAGE LEAKING (CHECKED ON FLIGHT 962-0750 DEPARTURE TO OAKLAND). BOTH CONTAINERS WERE PULLED FROM THE BELT FOR INSPECTION. WE OPENED THE CONTAINER AND NOTICED THE METAL FLASK WITHIN THE CONTAINER. IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED CSC (JEFF) FOR INSTRUCTION. CSC CONTACTED JOHN ANDRUS (SAFETY SPECIALIST).  MIKE WILLIAMS (CSA) WHO CHECKED IN THE PASSENGER AT THE TICKET COUNTER PAGED MARK ROBIEN (PASSENGER-CONFIRMATION NUMBER MRKM94) AT THE GATE. THE PASSENGER STATED THAT THE METAL FLASK HAD CONTAINED LIQUID NITROGEN, BUT WAS EMPTIED PRIOR TO SHIPMENT. WHAT WE WERE SEEING WAS THE CONDENSATION THAT WAS CREATED WITH THE AIR TEMPERATURE MIXING WITH THE COLD CONTAINER. NOTE: THE PASSENGER TOLD MIKE AT THE TIME OF CHECK-IN THAT IT CONTAINED SERUM, BUT WOULD NOT LEAK IF TIPPED (WAS GOING TO BE TIPPED GOING DOWN THE BELT). JOHN ANDRUS SUGGESTED THAT WE TRY TIPPING OVER THE CONTAINER (OUTSIDE) TO SEE IF ANYTHING LEAKS OUT OF THE METAL FLASK. LIQUID NITROGEN WAS RELEASED FROM THE CONTAINER AS SOON AS IT WAS TIPPED. CSC AND JOHN HAD ME CONTACT THE FAA FOR DISCLOSURE. THE PASSENGER AT THE GATE WAS INFORMED THAT HIS BAGGAGE WAS NOT GOING ON HIS FLIGHT. THE PASSENGER ( AND TWO TRAVELING WITH HIM) ELECTED NOT THE TRAVEL ON THEIR ORIGINAL FLIGHT (ACCOMMODATED ON FLIGHT 1721-1130 FLIGHT TO OAKLAND). CONTACTED THE 24-HOUR FAA LINE AND SPOKE WITH NANCY (COULD NOT GET A HOLD OF CASFO). HAD A CONFERENCE CALL WITH THOMAS KENNY(FAA - DANGEROUS GOODS). EXPLAINED WHAT WE KNEW ABOUT THE FLASK. THOMAS SAID HE WOULD MEET ME IN APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF HOUR TO INSPECT THE CONTENTS. TOOK BOTH CONTAINERS DOWN TO T-POINT FOR INSPECTION. IT WAS CONFIRMED THAT ONE OF THE TWO CONTAINERS STILL CONTAINED LIQUID NITROGEN. THOMAS TOOK PHOTOS AND REPORTS. I ASKED THOMAS IF WE WERE ABLE TO SHIP THE CONTAINERS WITH THE PASSENGERS OUT ON FLIGHT 1721. THOMAS SAID THAT IT WAS UP TO US. AS SOON AS THE PASSENGER DISPOSED OF THE EXISTING LIQUID NITROGEN OUT OF THE FLASK, BOTH CONTAINERS WOULD BE GOOD FOR SHIPMENT. CONTACTED CSC TO ENSURE PASSENGER WAS STILL GOOD TO TRAVEL. PASSENGER AND LUGGAGE WERE ACCOMMODATED ON FLIGHT 1721-1130 FLIGHT TO OAKLAND. WARREN DIESSNER (WEEKEND DUTY MANAGER), FRANK GUISTIANI (REGIONAL MANAGER) AND JACKIE STEVENS (STATION MANAGER) WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE COLTON DEPARTURE YARD. DEVELOPED AN FRA INSPECTOR WAS ON THE PROPERTY AND OBSERVED THE ABOVE CAR WITH FRESH PRODUCT ON THE TOP SURFACE AREA OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS ON TRACK #304 WHICH WAS AN ENTRAINED BNSF INTERCHANGE. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LOCATION, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM LOOSE MANWAY SWING BOLTS. THE MANWAY WAS OPENED AND THE GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION. THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE THEN PROPERLY TIGHTENED TO SECURE THE LADING. EVIDENCE OF A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS NOTED ON THE TOP SURFACE OF THE CAR FROM SPLASHING OUT OF THE MANWAY WHILE IN TRANSIT. THE STAINED AREA WAS EVAPORATING, AND IT APPEARED THAT NO PRODUCT DRIPPED TO THE GROUND. RMCC MADE THE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS.

column168: A UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD LOCOMOTIVE MANAGER REPORTED RAIL CAR UTLX79961, PARKED IN THE EAST RECEIVING YARD, TRACK 9, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THE LOAD WAS ASPHALT. MR. REIMERS ALSO STATED A CREW FROM R.M. CAT CONTRACTORS WAS ENROUTE TO THE LOCATION TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE LEAKING TANK CAR. UPON INSPECTION, RMCAT ADVISED THAT SIX OF THE EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE IN THE DOWN POSITION. THE TWO SWING BOLTS THAT WERE IN THE UP POSITION WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THIS RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND. REPRESENTATIVES FROM RMCAT TIGHTENED ALL EIGHT SWING BOLTS AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

AT 0700HRS ON 8-6-01, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT AN EMPLOYEE HAD COMPLAINED OF CHEST PAINS AND SORE THROAT BECAUSE OF WALKING BY 2 TANK CARS IN TRACK 205, SETTEGAST YARD, MILE POST 381, BEAUMONT SUBDIVISION; HOUSTON, TX. UPON EXPOSURE, EMPLOYEE R.B. LOTT; SWITCHMAN, REPORTED TO MYO CURT HUCKABY. MR. LOTT DECLINED ANY MEDICAL TREATMENT. INSPECTION OF CAR UTLX 803633, RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINING PETROLEUM DISTILLATE, UN1268; FAILED TO DEVELOP ANY SOURCE OF RELEASE. INSPECTION OF CAR PTLX 220153, LOADED WITH SODIUM HYDROSULFIDE SOLUTION, NA2922, REVEALED A SLIGHT RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM THE MAN WAY OPENING. PRODUCT WAS NOTED TO WITHIN THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND TOP PORTION OF THE CAR. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND. UPON DETERMINING SOURCE OF RELEASE, MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, LUBRIZOL, AND ADVISED MR. RON BEESON, NORTH AMERICAN TRANSPORTATION MANAGER OF THE INCIDENT AND CONDITION OF THE CAR. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE PLANT PERSONNEL INSPECT THE CAR. ON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF CAR BY LUBRIZOL PERSONNEL, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE MAN WAY COVER GASKET WAS WORN AND IN NEED OF REPLACEMENT. GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE MAN WAY COVER WAS RESECURED MAKING THE CAR SUITABLE FOR TRANSPORTATION. THE TOP OF THE CAR WAS WIPED OFF. NO FURTHER ACTION WAS NECESSARY.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING IM TANK AT THE ICTF IN LONG BEACH, CA. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE FACILITY, LOCATED THE ABOVE IM TANK AT E5, SPACE 298, AND FOUND A SMALL POOL (APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON) OF PRODUCT ON THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE TANK. INSPECTION NOTED AN INTERMITTENT DRIP FROM THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE JACKET. FIELD TESTING DEVELOPED THE LIQUID WAS PRODUCT. INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY COMPARTMENT AND VALVE COMPARTMENT SHOWED NO SIGNS OF ACCUMULATED PRODUCT. IT APPEARED THE TANK HAD FAILED AND THE PRODUCT WOULD REQUIRE TRANSFER TO A NEW VESSEL. CONTACT WITH SHIPPER PRODUCED A PRODUCT MSDS AND ADDITIONAL CONTACT WITH THE TANK OWNER, STOLT NEILSON. STOLT STATED THE TANK WAS LOADED FOR CELANESE BY PETRO UNITED, A BULK LIQUID STORAGE TERMINAL LOCATED IN SEABROOK, TX. STOLT MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH VENTURA LESBRO, THE LOCAL VENDOR FOR STOLT, TO PROVIDE A REPLACEMENT TANK, UTCU 459567. LATER IN THE AFTERNOON, THE TRANSFER OPERATION WAS COMPLETED, AND BOTH TANKS WERE MOVED TO THE VENTURA LESBRO FACILITY FOR LATER DELIVERY AND INSPECTION. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT COLTON, CA.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON RECEIVING YARD, LOCATED THE ABOVE TANK CAR IN TRACK #202, AND NOTED THE TOP WORK AREA OF THE CAR HAD RESIDUE PRODUCT ON THE SURFACE, NONE OF WHICH HAD RUN DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR.  INSPECTION FOUND THE VACUUM BREAKER VALVE, UNDER THE PROTECTIVE COVER FOR THE LIQUID AND VAPOR LINES , WAS DEFECTIVE. IT APPEARED THE VALVE HAD A DEFECTIVE GASKET PREVENTING IT FROM SEATING PROPERLY.  AS THERE WAS NO WAY TO REPAIR THE VALVE IN THE FIELD, THE VACUUM BREAKER WAS REMOVED AND A PIPE PLUG WAS INSTALLED IN IT'S PLACE TO SECURE THE PRODUCT IN THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE TEMPORARY REPAIR AND REQUESTED TO CONTACT THE CONSIGNEE TO PROTECT THE CAR WHILE OFF LOADING THE PRODUCT.  RMCC MADE THE NOTIFICATIONS.

column168: MANAGER DEAN C. COOPER DISCOVERED SUBJECT CAR LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY. DETERMINED THAT MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE. MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED FOR REPAIRS. SPILLAGE CONFINED TO TOP OF TANK CAR WITH NO ENVIRONMENTAL  DAMAGE. CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTER REPAIRS COMPLETED.

MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, CRAIG DENNY, WAS ADVISED THAT TANK CAR GATX 29022 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR EVERY TIME THAT IT WAS MOVED. MGR DENNY'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE RUBBER RUPTURE DISK COVER FLANGE HAD JUST ONE LOOSE BOLT HOLDING IT ON, INSTEAD OF THE THREE IT REQUIRES. IN ADDITION, THE CAP FOR THE COVER FLANGE WAS NOT IN PLACE, AND THE RUPTURE DISK WAS RUPTURED.  THE RESULT WAS A 2" UNOBSTRUCTED HOLE DIRECTLY INTO THE TANK.  THEREFORE, EVERYTIME THE CAR WAS MOVED, PRODUCT SLOSHED OUT OF THIS HOLE. MGR DENNY TIGHTENED THE RUBBER COVER FLANGE AND PLACED THE CAP IN THE FLANGE COVER AS REQUIRED, ALLOWING FOR THE CAR TO BE MOVED TO AN ADJACENT TRACK. BP AMOCO WAS CONTACTED AND WAS TO SEND A TEAM OUT OF TEXAS CITY TO REPLACE THE RUPTURE DISK AND REPLACE THE TWO MISSING BOLTS BEFORE THE CAR WOULD BE ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.
