column168: (A/B) ON 8/15/2001, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, DAVE JACKSON, WAS ADVISED BY RTS MANAGER BRADLEY MORINE THAT CONTAINER NOSU 447022 WAS LEAKING AN UNKNOWN MATERIAL FROM A PLACARDED SHIPMENT AT THE UP INTERMODAL FACILITY, LATHROP CALIFORNIA.  THE INITIAL ASSESSMENT INDICATED NO LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. UPON A CLOSEUP INSPECTION ON 8/20/2001 REVEALED ONE TOTE AND TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS WERE FOUND LEAKING. A TOTAL OF 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED FROM ALL THREE CONTAINERS. ANOTHER 70 GALLONS OF NON-REGULATED ZEP CLEANER 143 FROM TWO METAL DRUMS WAS FOUND TO BE GONE DUE TO THE TWO DRUMS THAT HAD RUBBED AGAINST THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER AND RUBBED THE CHIME OF THE DRUM TO THE POINT WHERE IT HAD BURNED THE INSIDE OF THE CONTAINER.  BOTH LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR OF CONTAINER NOSU 447022.  THE LOAD WAS FOUND TO HAVE INSUFFICIENT BLOCKING AND BRACING AT THE DOOR.  THE TYGUARD DID NOT MEET SPECIFICATIONS AND WAS LOOSE.  THERE WAS ALSO NO BUFFERING BETWEEN PALLETS TO HELP STOP RUBBING.  THE CONTAINER WAS ALSO FOUND WITH PALLETS BETWEEN PALLETS WITH NAILS PROTRUDING FROM THE PALLETS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TRANSLOADED BY MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL.  PHOTOS WERE TAKEN AND THE INSPECTION WAS MADE IN THE PRESENCE OF CALIFORNIA PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION TRANSPORTATION SUPERVISOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR DENNIS BIGGS.

LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED OF A TANK CAR OF CARBON DIOXIDE VENTING IN HERINGTON, KS.  TIMX 201033 WAS OBSERVED BY YARD PERSONNEL TO BE RELEASING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. MR. SEKAVEC ADVISED THEM TO LET THE CAR SET FOR ANOTHER HOUR OR SO AND THEN RECHECK THE CAR TO SEE IF THE RELIEF VALVE WOULD RESET.  THE CAR WAS CHECKED AFTER THE TIME HAD PASSED AND MR. SEKAVEC WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE CAR WAS STILL RELEASING PRODUCT.  MR. SEKAVEC TRAVELED TO HERINGTON AND BEGAN AN ASSESSMENT ON THE CAR.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LOWEST PRESSURE REGULATING VALVE WAS OPERATING.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH EPCO, THE SHIPPER OF THE CO2 TO ASCERTAIN IF A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE COMPANY WAS AVAILABLE AND ONE WAS WITH AN ETA OF APPROXIMATELY TWO HOURS.  ON ARRIVAL OF MR. LYNN BEARD OF EPCO, A CHECK WAS MADE OF THE CAR AGAIN AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT SOME OF THE ICE ON THE RELIEF VALVE HAD MELTED BUT THE VALVE WAS STILL VENTING GAS.  THE PRESSURE WAS CHECKED ON THE CAR AND FOUND TO BE APPROXIMATELY 330 PSI.  THE PROPER PRESSURE FOR THIS COMMODITY SHOULD HAVE BEEN APPROXIMATELY 250 PSI.  THE VAPOR VALVE ON THE CAR WAS OPENED AND PRODUCT WAS VENTED TO REDUCE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE. MR. BEARD STATED THAT THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED BASED ON THE PRESSURE AND THE FACT THE LIQUID CARBON DIOXIDE WAS COMING FROM THE VAPOR LINE.  THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO VENT UNTIL THE PRESSURE DROPPED TO 250 PSI.  THE CAR WAS RECHECKED AND IT WAS FOUND TO BE SECURE WITH ALL VENTING FROM THE REGULATING VALVE STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.

AT 1135 HRS ON 8-24-01, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, DICKEY FITZGERALD.  HE ADVISED THAT AN FRA INSPECTOR HAD REPORTED RESIDUE TANK CAR NATX 78391 TO BE VENTING.  CAR WAS LOCATED IN YARD 45, TRACK 401 GALENA PARK, TX.; MILEPOST 4.6, CLINT SUBDIVISION.  UPON RECEIVING INFORMATION, MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TEXMARK AND SPOKE TO MS LINDA SALINAS; ENVIRONMENT & SAFETY MANGER.  MGR LERCH ADVISED HER OF THE REPORTED CONDITION OF THE CAR, AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO INSPECT WITH A FACILITY LOADER.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CAR, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS FAULTY.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED WITH A TEMPORARY GORTEX GASKET WHICH SECURED THE TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  MGR LERCH THEN ADVISED MS SALINAS OF THE POOR GASKET CONDITION AND REVIEWED TANK CAR SECUREMENT PROCEDURES AS THEY WERE THE ORIGINAL LOADING FACILITY AND LESSOR OF THE CAR.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE GASKET REPLACED WITH A NEW GASKET UPON ARRIVAL OF THE CAR AT THEIR FACILITY.  CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE THAT RELEASED THE CAR AS A RESIDE EMPTY, REICHHOLD CHEMICAL, AND SPOKE TO A  MR HERALD BLOOM, LOADING MANAGER.  MGR LERCH ADVISED HIM OF THE INCIDENT AND TANK CAR INSPECTION PROCEDURES IN REGARDS TO RELEASING A RESIDUE EMPTY CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED AS THE RESULT OF THIS RELEASE.

ON FRIDAY, 8/24/01, PERSONNEL AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD YARD AT LIVONIA, LOUISIANA DETECTED THE SMELL OF AMMONIA AND OBSERVED A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 91878.  THE CAR WAS ON THE HUMP AND WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED IN TRACK 500 WITH OUT INCIDENT.  MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS KENNY GOMEZ NOTIFIED MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, T. M. ROBINSON WHO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. GOMEZ ALSO NOTIFIED THE RISK MANAGEMENT NOTIFICATION CENTER, WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER. UPON ARRIVAL, ROBINSON WAS MET BY TROOPER LEE LOUIS OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, HAZ-MAT UNIT.  ROBINSON AND TROOPER LOUIS INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID AMMONIA DRIPPING FROM THE PLUG ON THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE.  THE AMMONIA WAS IMMEDIATELY FLASHING OFF CAUSING A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD.  ROBINSON WAS ABLE TO TURN THE HANDWHEEL OF THE TWO INCH ANGLE VALVE APPROXIMATELY 1/16TH OF A TURN AND THIS STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE VALVE PLUG WAS FIRST LOOSENED AND THEN RETIGHTENED AFTER ALL OF THE LIQUID AMMONIA HAD FLASHED OFF.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  ROBINSON SPOKE WITH MR. ALLEN HAWKINS OF FIRST MISSISSIPPI CHEMICAL/TRIAD NITROGEN.  HAWKINS WAS GIVEN THE DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT AND RELATED THAT THE HE WOULD FOLLOW UP WITH PLANT PERSONNEL.

SLOANE RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED ON 55 GALLON DRUM OF A 72 DRUM LOAD THAT HAD BEEN PUNCTURED DUE TO A LOAD SHIFT.  THE LOAD SHIFT WAS THE RESULT OF IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING.  MR SLOANE ADVISED THE SHIPPER, APL, AND CONTACTED FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL FOR CLEAN UP AND TRANSFER OF THE CONTAINER.

column168: ON THURSDAY, 8/30/01, TANK CAR GATX 61130 WAS FOUND TO BE EMITTING A SMALL VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD YARD AT LIVONIA, LOUISIANA.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED IN TRACK 21 WITH OUT INCIDENT.  UPRR MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, MR KENNY GOMEZ NOTIFIED UPRR MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL  FIELD OPERATIONS T. M. ROBINSON AND THE UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER.  RMCC IN TURN NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, CHEMTREC AND REAGENT CHEMICAL, THE SHIPPER.  ROBINSON RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AS DID MR. RALPH MELANCON OF REAGENT CHEMICAL.  UPON ARRIVAL ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED BY MELANCON WHO ADVISED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM A FAILED 165 POUND FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  MELANCON HAD ALREADY REPLACED THE DISC AND THIS SECURED THE LEAK.  ROBINSON AND MELANCON REINSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT IT HAD PROPER OUTAGE, HOWEVER FOUND THAT IT DID NOT HAVE A BAFFLE BENEATH THE SAFETY VENT.  MELANCON HAD ONE IN HIS POSSESSION AND INSTALLED IT ONTO THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  ROBINSON INSTRUCTED RMCC TO UPDATE THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE ON THE RESOLUTION OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON 8/30/2001 AT 1936 HRS. KIM L KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPS, WAS NOTIFIED THAT A SUBSTANCE HAD LEAKED OUT OF TANK CAR GATX 300807 IN THE WEST BOWL ON TRACK 58.  THE SUBSTANCE HAD CONTAMINATED THE CLOTHING OF A UPRR EMPLOYEE, STEVE SCHAD, SENIOR MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED THE INCIDENT AND REQUESTED PROCEDURES FOR DEALING WITH THE EMPLOYEE.  HE WAS PROVIDED WITH THE APPROPRIATE MSDS INFORMATION.  RMCC CONTACTED CHEMTREC (REPORT NUMBER 08302001084 CONTACT DON).  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER (BETHLEHEM STEEL).  TOM CIVIC  (INDUSTRIAL HYGIENE MANAGER) CALLED US BACK AND STATED THAT EVERYTHING WE HAD DONE WITH THE EMPLOYEE WAS RIGHT AND THAT THIS PRODUCT WAS NOT HARMFUL.  MR. KEELING RESPONDED TO THE CAR AND FOUND APPROX 100 GALS OF WHAT APPEARED TO BE A PETROLEUM TAR ON THE GROUND AND ALL OVER THE TANK CAR.  TWO COVERED HOPPERS ADJACENT TO THE CAR WERE ALSO CONTAMINATED WITH THE SPRAY OF PRODUCT. AROUND 11PM TERRY KIRK WITH BETHLEHEM STEEL CALLED AND STATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS COAL TAR AND SHE DID NOT KNOW WHY IT WAS SHIPPED AS METHYL NAPTHALENE.  THE MANWAY BOLTS ON THIS CAR WERE COMPLETELY DISENGAGED AND THE MANWAY COULD NOT CONTAIN THE PRODUCT DURING HUMPING OPERATIONS, WHICH LED TO THE RELEASE.  MR. KEELING SECURED THE MANWAY BOLTS AND MOVED THE CAR TO THE SCRAP DOCK IN NORTH PLATTE BAILEY YARD TO BE CLEANED.  MOBILE RAIL SERVICE WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED WITH THEIR HIGH RAIL VAC TRUCK.  14 CUBIC YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WERE RECOVERED AND WERE DISPOSED OF ACCORDINGLY. THE TANK CAR SAFETY APPLIANCES WERE CONTAMINATED AND WERE SCHEDULED TO BE CLEANED BY HAZ-MAT RESPONSE INC. ON 9/1/2001.  HAZMAT RESPONSE IN CLEANED THE CAR AND IT WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION ON 9/3/2001.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE ICTF, LONG BEACH, CA. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE FACILITY, LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER ON RAILCAR DTTX 27202-A, AND NOTED A DARK LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE UNDER CARRIAGE NEAR THE REAR DOORS. FIELD TESTING WAS INCONCLUSIVE IN IDENTIFYING THE LIQUID AS THE LISTED HAZARDOUS COMMODITY. THE CONTAINER WAS 'DIAPERED' AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR ISOLATION AND INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, NOTED THE BLOCKING AND BRACING CONSISTED OF 2X4'S PLACED CROSSWISE INTO THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALLS OF THE CONTAINER, RATHER THAN AT THE BULL SLOTS PROVIDE AT THE REAR DOORS. DOUBLE STACKED PALLETS OF 5 GALLON POLY PAILS WERE ADJACENT TO THE LUMBER. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED METHOD OF SECUREMENT, NOR IS IT APPROVED PER THE AAR BOE PAMPHLET 6C  FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES TRANSPORTED BY RAIL. CLOSER INSPECTION NOTED NAILS HAD BEEN DRIVEN THROUGH THE 2X4'S, WHICH WENT THROUGH THE LUMBER AND INTO THE SIDES OF THE POLY PAILS. 4 PAILS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED AND RELEASED SEVERAL GALLONS OF PRODUCT EACH. THE SHIPPER ARRANGED TO HAVE TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL REMOVE THE LADING, CLEAN THE RESIDUE, AND PLACE THE LADING BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE LEAKING PAILS AND TWO ADDITIONAL DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK DRUM FOR SHIPMENT BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER. ONCE THE LADING WAS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  RMCC MAD ALL NOTIFICATIONS.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT PHOENIX, AZ.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE PHOENIX YARDMASTER AND DEVELOPED THE TRAIN CREW FROM THE LB432 REPORTED A TANK CAR IN THEIR CONSIST WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING MOVED IN YARD TRACK 01. DEVELOPED THE CAR HAD JUST BEEN PICKED UP FROM THE SHIPPER, ROMIC ENVIRONMENTAL, AND DELIVERED TO THE PHOENIX YARD. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND ADVISED THEM OF THE CURRENT LEAKING CONDITION OF THE CAR. ROMIC STATED THEY WOULD HAVE PLANT PERSONNEL RESPOND TO INSPECT THE CAR. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS FROM THE MANWAY WHILE THE CAR WAS IN MOTION, AND ALL EIGHT OF THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE TIGHT. UPON OPENING THE MANWAY, THE MANWAY GASKET WAS NOTED MISSING. A NEW MANWAY GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY PROPERLY SECURED. THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE. THE CAR WAS ALSO NOTED TO HAVE UN3082 PLACARDS SHOWING, WHICH WERE REMOVED AND THE CORRECT UN1993 PLACARDS INSTALLED. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER WORDS: ON AUG. 18TH AT APPROXIMATELY 200AM. I LOADED A LOAD OF GAS FOR #539 SHELL. I DROVE TO THE STATION. I HOOPED UP AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD. AFTER ABOUT 10 MINUTES I ATTEMPTED TO CHECK MY LINES. WHEN I BENT DOWN AND TURNED MY LIGHT ON IT FLASHED BACK IN MY FACE, I THEN ATTEMPTED TO PUT THE FIRE OUT. I THEN CALLED 911 AND WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL. JAMES AUSTIN  WESCOURT DIST HAD A OTHERDRIVER COME AND FINISH UNLOADING TANKER AT THAT TIME WE FOUND THAT THE MR. AUSTIN HAD PUT A METAL OBJECT IN THE UST VENT.  THIS IS WHERE THE VAPORS CAME FROM. THE FOLLOWING IS LETTER SENT TO ALL DRIVERS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER HOSE CAP GASKET WAS BAD AND LEAKED PRODUCT INTO DRAIN PAN.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP.  THE DRIVER WILL GET A GASKET FOR THE CAP AT THE TERMINAL.  NO FURTHER INCIDENTS, NO INJURIES. BENT DOWN AND TURNED MY LIGHT ON IT FLASHED BACK IN MY FACE.  I THEN ATTEMPTED TO PUT THE FIRE OUT.  I THEN CALLED 911 AND WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL.  JAMES AUSTIN. WESTCOURT DIST HAD ANOTHER DRIVER COME AND FINISH UNLOADING TANKER.  AT THAT TIME WE FOUND THAT MR. AUSTIN HAD PUT A METAL OBJECT IN THE UST VENT. THIS IS WHERE THE VAPORS CAME FROM.  THE FOLLOWING IS LETTER SENT TO ALL DRIVERS. WE MAY NEVER KNOW FOR SURE WHAT STARTED THIS FIRE, BUT WE ARE LOOKING AT THE POSSIBILITY OF STATIC ELECTRICITY.  WE DO KNOW WHERE THE VAPORS CAME FROM.  EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY WE NO LONGER PUT ANYTHING IN THE VAPOR VENT TO HOLD IT OPEN.  WE WILL ALSO PARK OUR TRUCK SO THAT VAPOR VENT IS NOT UNDER THE TRUCK OR TRAILER.  IF YOU NEED MORE HOSE OR FITTINGS TO HOOK UP THE VAPOR VENT STOP BY BASIN AND PICK THEM UP AND HAVE ALL YOUR HOSES CHECKED FOR CONDUCTIVITY.  YOUR HOSES ARE YOUR GROUND.  WE HAVE ORDERED STATIC STRIPS TO BE ADDED TO ALL TRAILERS.  WE WILL HAVE JAY PUT THEM ON.  BE HERE 8/22.  I HAVE ORDERED NEW EXPLOSION PROOF FLASHLIGHTS.  SHOULD BE HERE ABOUT 8/23.  NO OTHER TYPE FLASHLIGHTS WILL BE ALLOWED IN TRUCKS.  YOU MUST NOT WARE ANY POLYESTER, NYLON OR OTHER HIGHLY FLAMMABLE MATERIALS.  COTTON BEST.  HAVE ORDERED FLAME RESISTANT JACKETS TO BE WORN WHEN LOADING OR UNLOADING AT ALL TIMES.  BE HERE 08/22.  NO LONG HAIR (OR MUST BE IN PONYTAIL (UNDER HAT) NO FACIAL HAIR.  SHORT MUSTACHE ONLY.  LOOKING FOR BETTER GLOVES WILL LET YOU KNOW.  NO JUMPING THE SCULLY SYSTEM, YOU WILL PUT THE TRAILER OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL IT IS FIXED. WE HAVE TWO EXTRA TRAILERS.  IF ANY OF YOU HAVE ANY IDEAS THAT YOU CAN ADD TO OUR SAFETY, PLEASE CALL ME.  THANK YOU, BE SAFE. DARRELL.

AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY THE DRIVER FOUND ONE DRUM WITH A CRACK IN A DENT IN ITS LOWER ROLLING HOOP. THE DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN JAMMED IN DURING LOADING. ABOUT 1/3 OF THE CONTENTS HAS BEEN LOST, MOST OF WHICH HAS RUN UP THROUGH THE TRAILER AND UNDER OTHER FREIGHT. THE TRAILER WILL HAVE TO BE UNLOADED IN ORDER TO BE CLEANED. THERE IS NO SPACE FOR THE TRUCK TO BE PARKED WHERE IT IS, NOR DO THEY HAVE ANY DOCK SPACE THERE TO UNLOAD ONTO. CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN ALLOWED THE DRIVER TO TAKE THE TRUCK TO A NEARBY TRUCK STOP. THE DRIVER TURNED THE DRUM ONTO IS SIDE AND SECURED IT TO THE WALL. HE REPORTS THAT THERE IS NO MORE STANDING LIQUID ON TRAILER FLOOR. HE NOW BELIEVES THAT HE CAN SAFELY CONTINUE TO J1. THE HAZMAT TECHNICIAN AGREED AND INSTRUCTED HIM TO DO SO BUT TO CLOSELY MONITOR THE TRAILER WHILE HE IS ENROUTE. VEHICLE ARRIVED AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.
WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE, THE FORKLIFT RIPPED THE BAG CAUSING IT TO LEAK.  THE CUSTOMER ACCEPTED ENTIRE FREIGHT SHIPMENT.
NON TRANSPORTATIONAL INCIDENT. #2 HOME HEATING OIL RELEASED WHILE FILLING HOME HEATING OIL TANK.
